WEBVTT

1
00:00:24.407 --> 00:00:29.276
Michael Jackson's LA Residence
June 25. 2009

2
00:01:21.527 --> 00:01:24.439
I arrived at the hospital

3
00:01:24.527 --> 00:01:25.516
Frank Dileo
JACKSON'S MANAGER 1984-89. 2009

4
00:01:25.647 --> 00:01:27.478
and the lady came out
maybe 20 minutes later. a nurse.

5
00:01:28.727 --> 00:01:31.400
I stood up. She said. "Who are you?"

6
00:01:32.567 --> 00:01:35.161
"I'm Frank Dileo. I manage Michael.

7
00:01:35.247 --> 00:01:36.566
"Is he okay?"

8
00:01:36.647 --> 00:01:39.286
She hesitated. and I knew.

9
00:01:40.167 --> 00:01:42.601
She looked me in the eye and said.

10
00:01:43.127 --> 00:01:44.526
"No. he didn't make it."

11
00:01:46.967 --> 00:01:49.720
I had them put him in a special room
and clean him up.

12
00:01:50.247 --> 00:01:55.958
And that was the one nice thing.
is I got to be alone with him.

13
00:01:57.247 --> 00:02:03.686
And I got to kiss him on the forehead
and. you know. tell him what I felt.

14
00:02:40.087 --> 00:02:41.281
When I started seeing the news clips

15
00:02:41.367 --> 00:02:43.642
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

16
00:02:43.727 --> 00:02:45.638
the day he died.

17
00:02:45.727 --> 00:02:46.842
my heart sank.

18
00:02:48.927 --> 00:02:54.126
Michael was the most exciting performer

19
00:02:54.207 --> 00:02:56.562
I had ever seen in my life.

20
00:02:58.647 --> 00:03:02.037
He was the ultimate pop superstar.

21
00:03:03.487 --> 00:03:06.524
He wanted. more than anything.
for his legacy to be

22
00:03:06.607 --> 00:03:09.758
he is the greatest performer of all time.

23
00:03:09.847 --> 00:03:11.360
And that's what he became.

24
00:04:23.687 --> 00:04:25.962
I grew up in East Chicago. Indiana.

25
00:04:28.327 --> 00:04:29.316
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

26
00:04:29.407 --> 00:04:32.126
My mother and father divorced when
I was at a young age. about six years old.

27
00:04:33.727 --> 00:04:34.955
My mother was Baptist.

28
00:04:35.047 --> 00:04:37.845
And my sister and I sang
in the Baptist choir.

29
00:04:38.647 --> 00:04:41.036
It made us have a love for music.

30
00:04:43.447 --> 00:04:46.883
My father used to listen
to the country music all the time.

31
00:04:46.967 --> 00:04:52.519
and out of Chicago came a show.
on the radio. called Suppertime Frolic.

32
00:04:55.127 --> 00:04:57.960
And then on Saturdays.
he would listen to the Grand Ole Opry

33
00:04:58.367 --> 00:04:59.800
that came out of Nashville.

34
00:05:01.047 --> 00:05:04.926
Some of the people were Ernest Tubb.
that's ancient.

35
00:05:05.007 --> 00:05:07.680
Let me... Let the people know how old I am.

36
00:05:11.807 --> 00:05:14.446
We had a club called the Sub-Debs.

37
00:05:20.047 --> 00:05:23.756
We used to give teenage parties
for all the kids around there.

38
00:05:24.127 --> 00:05:25.196
and that's where I met Joe.

39
00:05:27.567 --> 00:05:30.161
I think I was around 17 years old.

40
00:05:30.567 --> 00:05:35.595
He would always ask me for a dance
when the music was slow.

41
00:05:38.687 --> 00:05:41.121
He seemed very kind. very sweet.

42
00:05:44.287 --> 00:05:45.606
Joseph was in a group.

43
00:05:45.967 --> 00:05:50.279
Besides me leaving singing with my sister.
I started singing with him.

44
00:05:50.887 --> 00:05:54.277
And we would sing
and harmonise together a lot.

45
00:05:57.207 --> 00:06:00.244
Then the children came along.
and I kept singing.

46
00:06:03.567 --> 00:06:04.602
Rebbie Jackson
MICHAEL'S SISTER

47
00:06:04.687 --> 00:06:06.518
2300 Jackson St.
in that little house.

48
00:06:06.607 --> 00:06:09.201
I was the only one born in that house.

49
00:06:09.447 --> 00:06:11.563
We had two bedrooms in our home.

50
00:06:12.327 --> 00:06:15.603
And I and my sisters. Janet and La Toya.
slept in the living room.

51
00:06:15.687 --> 00:06:17.837
Living Room
Gary. Indiana 2010

52
00:06:17.927 --> 00:06:19.883
We had a couch that let out into a bed.

53
00:06:19.967 --> 00:06:21.719
My brothers slept in one room.

54
00:06:21.807 --> 00:06:23.320
Boy's Bedroom
Gary. Indiana 2010

55
00:06:23.407 --> 00:06:25.204
And that room had triple bunk beds.

56
00:06:25.287 --> 00:06:27.198
And they slept on the bunk beds.

57
00:06:27.287 --> 00:06:29.437
And then my parents slept in the other room.

58
00:06:29.527 --> 00:06:31.358
Parents' Bedroom
GARY. INDIANA 2010

59
00:06:31.447 --> 00:06:34.166
I don't know how I squeezed
all of us in that little house.

60
00:06:34.247 --> 00:06:35.236
Jackson Family Kitchen
Gary. Indiana 1960's

61
00:06:35.367 --> 00:06:39.042
Having all my children when I was young
and having them so close together.

62
00:06:40.287 --> 00:06:46.362
every time I would get pregnant.
I was afraid to tell Joe.

63
00:06:48.167 --> 00:06:53.002
We didn't believe in abortion.
so that's why we got so many children.

64
00:06:55.367 --> 00:06:58.040
The children around our neighbourhood.
especially the boys.

65
00:06:58.407 --> 00:06:59.681
they were kind of bad. some of them.

66
00:06:59.767 --> 00:07:02.645
They would break in people's cars
and do things.

67
00:07:02.727 --> 00:07:07.005
And our children were never allowed
to go out at night or play with those kids.

68
00:07:07.407 --> 00:07:08.806
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON'S FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

69
00:07:08.887 --> 00:07:11.799
They weren't really social
with the rest of the neighbourhood.

70
00:07:11.927 --> 00:07:16.125
They clung to each other.
and that's how the Jacksons were raised.

71
00:07:16.287 --> 00:07:18.847
Poor? I mean. that was a way of life.

72
00:07:18.927 --> 00:07:20.326
We had plenty of food to eat.

73
00:07:20.407 --> 00:07:22.523
We were like all the other kids in the area.

74
00:07:22.607 --> 00:07:24.916
DAVID Michael never thought
he was poor when he was young.

75
00:07:25.007 --> 00:07:27.077
because he did not know what poor was.

76
00:07:27.167 --> 00:07:28.236
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

77
00:07:28.327 --> 00:07:31.558
He thought
everyone lived the way his family did.

78
00:07:32.007 --> 00:07:34.396
We had
a rickety washing machine.

79
00:07:34.487 --> 00:07:35.806
We weren't able to buy a new one.

80
00:07:36.047 --> 00:07:38.242
Whenever it washed. it would creak.
You know. make noises...

81
00:07:39.927 --> 00:07:41.280
Something like that.

82
00:07:41.367 --> 00:07:44.643
And Michael. I guess.
was about 11 or 12 months old.

83
00:07:44.727 --> 00:07:47.287
He was just dancing
to the rhythm of the washing machine.

84
00:07:47.567 --> 00:07:49.797
And I knew then that he had a lot of rhythm.

85
00:07:54.407 --> 00:07:57.399
Michael would always do funny things.
anything for a laugh.

86
00:07:57.487 --> 00:07:58.806
Anything for a laugh.

87
00:08:00.127 --> 00:08:04.200
La Toya was always very persnickety
about the way she kept her room.

88
00:08:04.287 --> 00:08:05.402
And she had this beautiful...

89
00:08:05.487 --> 00:08:08.524
I think it was a white satin bedspread
that she had just gotten.

90
00:08:09.487 --> 00:08:11.682
Michael took some invisible ink

91
00:08:11.767 --> 00:08:14.645
and he spread it all over the bedspread.
squirted it all over.

92
00:08:14.727 --> 00:08:17.195
And then he had her come in
and look at it. She was livid.

93
00:08:19.847 --> 00:08:23.396
Michael used to love telling me stories
about Gary. Indiana.

94
00:08:23.487 --> 00:08:25.876
especially how he would have a candy store.

95
00:08:25.967 --> 00:08:28.606
and he would sell candy
to all the neighbours.

96
00:08:29.047 --> 00:08:30.765
and to his brothers.

97
00:08:30.847 --> 00:08:33.805
And he never made any money doing it.

98
00:08:33.887 --> 00:08:39.883
but he showed signs of being
an entrepreneur at a very young age.

99
00:08:40.127 --> 00:08:41.526
As kids. we had a lot of fun.

100
00:08:41.607 --> 00:08:42.676
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

101
00:08:42.807 --> 00:08:44.923
You know. just playing around
in the neighbourhood.

102
00:08:45.007 --> 00:08:49.478
Playing practical jokes. throwing balloons
out the car windows at bus stops.

103
00:08:49.727 --> 00:08:53.322
singing and dancing to every song
that came on the radio.

104
00:08:56.087 --> 00:08:58.999
Michael would use
some of the money from his candy store

105
00:08:59.087 --> 00:09:00.918
to go and buy 45s.

106
00:09:01.007 --> 00:09:04.556
because in those days.
that's what kids bought. 45s.

107
00:09:04.647 --> 00:09:07.366
And if you were lucky. you'd buy an LP.

108
00:09:07.527 --> 00:09:11.236
But he started listening strongly
to James Brown

109
00:09:11.767 --> 00:09:14.565
from the time he was about five years old.

110
00:09:14.647 --> 00:09:19.402
He had a great taste for real R&B.

111
00:09:19.487 --> 00:09:21.796
gritty R&B. like Wilson Pickett.

112
00:09:23.327 --> 00:09:25.045
the Dells.

113
00:09:25.127 --> 00:09:28.039
great singers like Levi Stubbs.

114
00:09:29.807 --> 00:09:33.117
We sang country songs
and we sang folk songs.

115
00:09:33.487 --> 00:09:36.285
And then
they started singing the Temptations

116
00:09:36.367 --> 00:09:38.517
when we got a television.

117
00:09:38.967 --> 00:09:42.482
My father had a guitar
that he kept locked in the closet.

118
00:09:42.567 --> 00:09:45.684
One day. he didn't lock the closet
and I started playing that thing.

119
00:09:45.767 --> 00:09:49.840
I learnt every song on the radio
and made my brothers sing with me.

120
00:09:49.927 --> 00:09:52.361
Joseph had warned them.
"Don't play my guitar. now."

121
00:09:52.647 --> 00:09:57.277
And so. Tito took it out and played it.
and a string broke.

122
00:09:57.887 --> 00:10:01.084
There was no way of hiding
that he hadn't had his guitar.

123
00:10:01.167 --> 00:10:02.566
He punished him for it.

124
00:10:02.647 --> 00:10:04.478
Then he said. "Let me hear you play."

125
00:10:04.567 --> 00:10:06.797
And Tito played for him.

126
00:10:06.887 --> 00:10:09.959
Joe just said nothing else to him.
"You can play it if you want to."

127
00:10:10.687 --> 00:10:13.838
Tito had been watching his father
play guitar.

128
00:10:13.927 --> 00:10:16.441
but he would come to my house
and he and I would play.

129
00:10:16.527 --> 00:10:17.642
Reynaud Jones
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

130
00:10:17.887 --> 00:10:20.959
And I would play a little something
on my guitar. and then show him.

131
00:10:21.047 --> 00:10:22.878
and then give my guitar to him.

132
00:10:23.087 --> 00:10:24.486
And then he'd try to play it.

133
00:10:24.567 --> 00:10:27.035
And so we went back and forth like that.

134
00:10:27.127 --> 00:10:30.836
There was a guy across the street
who had one snare drum.

135
00:10:31.327 --> 00:10:32.840
and his name was Milford Hite.

136
00:10:33.647 --> 00:10:34.716
Milford Hite
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

137
00:10:34.807 --> 00:10:36.160
Reynaud said.
"Milford. come over with your drum

138
00:10:36.247 --> 00:10:38.920
"and let's see if we can. you know.
start a little group together."

139
00:10:39.127 --> 00:10:41.516
We played for a while
and then Jackie Jackson came over.

140
00:10:41.847 --> 00:10:42.836
Okay.

141
00:10:43.007 --> 00:10:46.283
Then after Jackie came in. Jermaine came.

142
00:10:46.647 --> 00:10:48.558
Michael and Marlon were just little kids.

143
00:10:48.887 --> 00:10:51.481
And we used to tell them to be quiet.
"Get out of here."

144
00:10:51.567 --> 00:10:52.716
We used to kick them out the room.

145
00:10:52.807 --> 00:10:55.367
And they used to beg to be in the group.

146
00:10:55.447 --> 00:10:57.802
And we just said.
"Your little brother wants to be in the..."

147
00:10:57.887 --> 00:11:01.243
You know. you just said. "No. get out of here.
This is big boy stuff."

148
00:11:02.047 --> 00:11:06.563
The school was giving a programme
and all the parents were invited.

149
00:11:07.047 --> 00:11:10.357
And Michael was singing solo.
Climb Every Mountain.

150
00:11:10.447 --> 00:11:14.122
And so Joe's father wanted to go also.
so he could hear him.

151
00:11:15.007 --> 00:11:17.043
And Michael starts singing.

152
00:11:17.447 --> 00:11:20.245
I looked around. Joe's father was crying.

153
00:11:22.127 --> 00:11:23.606
I guess he couldn't imagine

154
00:11:23.687 --> 00:11:27.123
that a 5-year-old kid can keep harmony
and sing that well.

155
00:11:27.207 --> 00:11:28.322
But that's what happened.

156
00:11:28.847 --> 00:11:33.204
We heard him sing
and we were so taken by that.

157
00:11:33.967 --> 00:11:36.037
We couldn't believe it
so we rushed him home.

158
00:11:36.127 --> 00:11:37.879
immediately took him to the room.

159
00:11:37.967 --> 00:11:40.197
And he was in the group. that fast.

160
00:11:43.207 --> 00:11:47.962
The big thing back then was winning
the Roosevelt High School talent show.

161
00:11:48.287 --> 00:11:49.686
In the '50s and the '60s.

162
00:11:49.767 --> 00:11:55.205
talent shows were the key
to getting a career and a record deal.

163
00:11:55.487 --> 00:11:57.796
And that's what they dreamed of.

164
00:11:58.927 --> 00:12:01.964
Initially. Michael was not our lead singer.

165
00:12:02.047 --> 00:12:06.643
It was Jermaine was our lead singer
when we made it to the talent show.

166
00:12:07.207 --> 00:12:10.597
They came to me and asked me
if I would come over

167
00:12:10.687 --> 00:12:11.676
Robert Hite
NEIGHBOUR - GARY. INDIANA

168
00:12:11.807 --> 00:12:14.480
and give them some pointers
on tightening up the group.

169
00:12:14.567 --> 00:12:19.800
I actually decided that we were going
to present the song My Girl.

170
00:12:19.887 --> 00:12:24.278
because it was a song
that I had become very fond of.

171
00:12:24.767 --> 00:12:28.442
Each person would get a chance
to step forward in the song.

172
00:12:28.527 --> 00:12:30.245
and showcase what they could do.

173
00:12:30.447 --> 00:12:33.996
Milford actually sang My Girl along
with them.

174
00:12:34.087 --> 00:12:36.043
Reynaud was singing My Girl.

175
00:12:36.127 --> 00:12:40.405
And all of a sudden we said.
"Michael. sing My Girl."

176
00:12:40.487 --> 00:12:43.797
And he hit it. perfect pitch.

177
00:12:45.207 --> 00:12:46.401
And that was it.

178
00:12:46.487 --> 00:12:48.557
That was our secret weapon. quite honestly.

179
00:12:58.927 --> 00:13:01.202
When Michael came in.
the crowd just stood up.

180
00:13:03.007 --> 00:13:06.363
They actually broke a couple of chairs
and seats in the auditorium.

181
00:13:12.607 --> 00:13:14.882
It was such a surprise.

182
00:13:14.967 --> 00:13:18.198
And that's when everybody recognised
the kind of talent that was there.

183
00:13:21.287 --> 00:13:23.721
We wanted to win and we won.

184
00:13:24.287 --> 00:13:25.481
It was a really happy moment.

185
00:13:25.567 --> 00:13:28.798
It was just... 'Cause that was the thing to win.
Roosevelt's talent show.

186
00:13:28.887 --> 00:13:31.481
We win a Roosevelt's talent show.
it's like signing a contract with Motown.

187
00:13:37.087 --> 00:13:39.203
After the talent show ended.

188
00:13:39.287 --> 00:13:45.078
Joe decided that Reynaud and Milford
weren't going to be rehearsing with them.

189
00:13:46.007 --> 00:13:48.077
And that's what kind of split everything off.

190
00:13:51.807 --> 00:13:54.879
Joseph was. in many ways.
a frustrated musician.

191
00:13:54.967 --> 00:13:57.197
He had a band called the Falcons.

192
00:13:57.287 --> 00:14:02.998
And I think to some extent
he wanted to live vicariously

193
00:14:03.087 --> 00:14:06.762
through the success. the possible success.
of his children as musicians.

194
00:14:07.527 --> 00:14:09.324
But Joseph is a very complicated person.

195
00:14:09.407 --> 00:14:12.444
and it's not easy to paint Joseph
with a wide brushstroke.

196
00:14:13.087 --> 00:14:14.076
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY I MOTOWN RECORDS

197
00:14:14.167 --> 00:14:15.759
Joe was a tyrant to them.

198
00:14:15.847 --> 00:14:18.361
He was mean to them. He was evil to them.

199
00:14:19.047 --> 00:14:21.686
Michael was very afraid of Joe.

200
00:14:21.767 --> 00:14:24.042
and a lot of times.
he would stay over at my house.

201
00:14:24.127 --> 00:14:26.197
just to get away from Joe.

202
00:14:26.287 --> 00:14:32.283
because he felt Joe had punished him
too much when he was younger.

203
00:14:33.367 --> 00:14:36.404
He had taken a strap
and spanked him a lot of times.

204
00:14:36.487 --> 00:14:38.876
And he felt it was too harsh.

205
00:14:39.047 --> 00:14:44.758
He was a very strong. and often.
as they would tell it. violent disciplinarian.

206
00:14:48.767 --> 00:14:54.125
Michael. Janet and Randy.
and a little bit of Marlon.

207
00:14:55.207 --> 00:14:59.678
I think they got easy street.
'cause they were the babies.

208
00:15:00.447 --> 00:15:04.486
The ones who really got the spankings
in my family. if I remember correctly.

209
00:15:04.567 --> 00:15:05.886
and I'm pretty sure I do.

210
00:15:05.967 --> 00:15:11.280
was myself. Jermaine and Jackie.
the older guys.

211
00:15:11.687 --> 00:15:14.759
I'm sort of like five years older than Michael.

212
00:15:14.847 --> 00:15:19.398
So he was more of one of the little guys
that didn't get it the way the big guys did.

213
00:15:19.807 --> 00:15:21.126
I think in later life.

214
00:15:22.687 --> 00:15:25.326
he began to respect Joe more.

215
00:15:25.407 --> 00:15:30.083
because he saw
that he wanted his kids to be somebody.

216
00:15:31.207 --> 00:15:33.277
RONALD JACKSON:
My uncle worked in the steel mill.

217
00:15:33.367 --> 00:15:36.916
He never wanted his kids to do what he did.
He wanted them to be better.

218
00:15:37.527 --> 00:15:38.596
Ronald & Keith Jackson
JACKSON'S FIRST COUSINS

219
00:15:38.727 --> 00:15:39.921
I seen the steel mill. and I'm gonna tell you...

220
00:15:40.007 --> 00:15:41.838
- It's like working for Satan...
- Do not work there...

221
00:15:41.927 --> 00:15:44.725
...because it's 2.000 degrees out there.
and it's very dangerous.

222
00:15:45.447 --> 00:15:47.483
So. his vision. I respect.

223
00:15:48.087 --> 00:15:52.763
He wanted them to have a better opportunity.
and to do something they love doing.

224
00:15:56.047 --> 00:16:00.199
I think Joe did the right thing
because none of his kids went to prison.

225
00:16:00.287 --> 00:16:03.359
None of his kids were out
on the street using dope.

226
00:16:04.727 --> 00:16:06.638
I think I was raised right.

227
00:16:06.727 --> 00:16:11.323
I think my father did a brilliant job
to take us from Gary. Indiana.

228
00:16:11.407 --> 00:16:16.117
which is a very poverty-stricken town.

229
00:16:16.207 --> 00:16:20.359
and not too many people get out of there
and make something of themselves.

230
00:16:20.647 --> 00:16:23.036
and he had a dream. and he stuck with it.

231
00:16:23.127 --> 00:16:26.278
And he knew how to get there
and he got us there.

232
00:16:26.887 --> 00:16:30.323
It's okay to have fun sometimes
but you have to prepare yourself.

233
00:16:30.407 --> 00:16:34.525
because your adulthood
is gonna be a lot longer than your childhood.

234
00:16:34.727 --> 00:16:38.037
And if you didn't prepare for it.
you're gonna be on The Late Show.

235
00:16:38.647 --> 00:16:43.402
So I think my father prepared his sons
for the future. to be men.

236
00:16:43.487 --> 00:16:46.365
We were men at a very young age.

237
00:16:46.447 --> 00:16:49.883
I remember asking Michael.
"Why do you call him Joseph?"

238
00:16:49.967 --> 00:16:53.437
And it was really clear.
the way Michael explained it.

239
00:16:53.527 --> 00:16:55.040
that they thought of him as Joseph.

240
00:16:55.487 --> 00:16:58.285
They didn't really think of him as their father.
they thought of him as Joseph.

241
00:16:58.367 --> 00:17:00.835
And I thought that was very sad.

242
00:17:01.127 --> 00:17:02.799
That had to hurt even Joseph.

243
00:17:02.887 --> 00:17:05.037
to know that his children
felt that way about him.

244
00:17:05.127 --> 00:17:08.597
but that was the way he designed it.

245
00:17:09.567 --> 00:17:10.556
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

246
00:17:10.687 --> 00:17:12.200
The world now talks
about how mean and evil he is.

247
00:17:12.287 --> 00:17:13.322
He's not that way.

248
00:17:14.487 --> 00:17:16.842
He's just a firm person.

249
00:17:19.967 --> 00:17:25.280
Michael's very close to my mother.
and she was like a comfort to him. I think.

250
00:17:26.367 --> 00:17:28.927
Michael and I had
a very special bond.

251
00:17:29.007 --> 00:17:33.159
Michael used to always tell me
that he was so much like me.

252
00:17:33.487 --> 00:17:36.081
And then I used to tell him. I said.

253
00:17:36.167 --> 00:17:40.843
"I can see myself in you.
but I don't want you to be like me."

254
00:17:40.927 --> 00:17:44.158
because I thought I was too easy-going.

255
00:17:44.247 --> 00:17:45.805
trust people too much.

256
00:17:45.887 --> 00:17:48.037
and that's exactly how Michael is.

257
00:17:49.527 --> 00:17:54.681
There was a mystical connection
that made them almost. at times. one.

258
00:17:55.207 --> 00:17:58.404
Michael and Katherine. two peas in a pod.

259
00:18:01.447 --> 00:18:04.519
He was closer to no one else except for her.

260
00:18:06.287 --> 00:18:09.723
Katherine Jackson
was golden where Michael was concerned.

261
00:18:09.927 --> 00:18:11.645
throughout his entire lifetime.

262
00:18:11.727 --> 00:18:12.716
She always cared.

263
00:18:12.807 --> 00:18:17.756
When he went through stages of acne.
she knew how to handle him.

264
00:18:18.807 --> 00:18:21.958
It was almost
as if they were

265
00:18:22.047 --> 00:18:24.561
aligned with each other against the world.

266
00:18:24.927 --> 00:18:27.680
And he could always go to Katherine
for anything.

267
00:18:27.767 --> 00:18:30.235
And she would be there for him. 100%.

268
00:18:41.807 --> 00:18:45.561
They had been working on the music
for a long time.

269
00:18:45.927 --> 00:18:48.316
and they wanted to be signed to a label.

270
00:18:49.287 --> 00:18:51.437
We would go to school in the morning.

271
00:18:52.127 --> 00:18:54.721
Then after school.
we'd get home about 3:00. 3:330.

272
00:18:55.447 --> 00:18:59.679
And my father'd have all the mics set up
and amps on standby.

273
00:19:00.567 --> 00:19:03.001
And we had enough time
to just drop our books.

274
00:19:03.087 --> 00:19:08.798
and we would practise. like. four hours.

275
00:19:08.887 --> 00:19:10.559
until about 7:00 or 8:00.

276
00:19:10.647 --> 00:19:12.399
And after that.

277
00:19:12.487 --> 00:19:14.762
we would get ready
to go to Chicago or somewhere.

278
00:19:14.847 --> 00:19:16.917
and go do an engagement.

279
00:19:17.127 --> 00:19:18.765
We would play for 45 minutes.

280
00:19:18.847 --> 00:19:22.396
and take 15 minutes off
and do our homework.

281
00:19:23.687 --> 00:19:27.999
By the time we was through with our day.
it was about 2:30 in the morning.

282
00:19:28.527 --> 00:19:33.362
And we'd drive back from Chicago to Gary.
get home about 3:00. 4:00 in the morning.

283
00:19:33.447 --> 00:19:35.244
then go to school the next day.

284
00:19:35.327 --> 00:19:38.399
And that's what life was for us
for many years. a lot of work.

285
00:19:39.807 --> 00:19:41.798
We would perform all night.
tell you the truth. every day.

286
00:19:41.887 --> 00:19:44.196
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

287
00:19:44.287 --> 00:19:46.403
We would be dancing. doing James Brown.

288
00:19:46.487 --> 00:19:50.002
and a lot of people throwing money on stage.
and standing ovations.

289
00:19:50.487 --> 00:19:54.036
And then. soon as we drove home.
we'd get up and go to school.

290
00:19:54.127 --> 00:19:58.166
And we couldn't keep our pants up
'cause we had so much money in 'em.

291
00:19:58.247 --> 00:20:00.317
I mean. change just broke 'em.

292
00:20:00.487 --> 00:20:02.717
And there was this man's house.
who used to sell candy.

293
00:20:02.807 --> 00:20:06.959
we used to stop there and just load up.
eat candy for days.

294
00:20:08.127 --> 00:20:10.880
They had a studio at home
and they had these big mirrors and stuff.

295
00:20:10.967 --> 00:20:14.676
And they would say. "Do it again.
do it again. do it again. do it again."

296
00:20:14.767 --> 00:20:18.282
And next thing you know.
seven. eight. nine hours go by.

297
00:20:18.367 --> 00:20:21.006
but they were looking for perfection.

298
00:20:21.407 --> 00:20:22.556
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST. 'JACKSON 5' 1967-77

299
00:20:22.647 --> 00:20:24.603
They were focused.
that's what I liked about them.

300
00:20:24.687 --> 00:20:28.123
They were serious about doing it.
and it was about perfection.

301
00:20:28.327 --> 00:20:33.447
Johnny Jackson and Ronnie Rancifer
were part of the early Jackson 5.

302
00:20:34.127 --> 00:20:37.915
They were not named members

303
00:20:38.007 --> 00:20:41.556
but they were a part of the group.
and an integral part of the group.

304
00:20:41.647 --> 00:20:45.083
Back then. we didn't have
the greatest instruments in the world.

305
00:20:45.527 --> 00:20:49.918
Other big name groups.
they would have big PAs and all that.

306
00:20:50.287 --> 00:20:52.926
Jacksons didn't have that.
but what they had was soul.

307
00:20:53.687 --> 00:20:55.564
See... And soul goes a long way.

308
00:20:55.647 --> 00:20:58.366
You can have $10 jillion
worth of equipment. baby.

309
00:20:58.447 --> 00:21:02.440
but if you ain't got no soul.
you might as well stay home.

310
00:21:03.287 --> 00:21:07.838
In 1967 the Jackson 5 signed for local
record label. Steeltown Records.

311
00:21:08.447 --> 00:21:10.085
[Skipped item nr. 329]

312
00:21:08.447 --> 00:21:10.085
They released two songs on the label;
'Big Boy'

313
00:21:10.167 --> 00:21:11.964
and 'We Don't Have To Be Over 21
(To Fall In Love).

314
00:21:12.047 --> 00:21:14.880
Neither appeared on any Billboard Chart.

315
00:21:18.687 --> 00:21:23.317
One day. I was setting up a VIP section
for Bobby Taylor.

316
00:21:23.727 --> 00:21:26.525
all of a sudden. I hear the people clapping
and hollering...

317
00:21:26.687 --> 00:21:28.882
Weldon Arthur McDougal III - A & R
EXECUTIVE. MOTOWN RECORDS 1969-80

318
00:21:28.967 --> 00:21:32.084
And so I come out of the office and I look
and there was the Jackson 5.

319
00:21:32.167 --> 00:21:34.078
Well. they are pretty good.

320
00:21:36.567 --> 00:21:39.764
Joe Jackson said.
"Listen. man. we wanna be on Motown."

321
00:21:39.847 --> 00:21:42.520
And I said.
"Man. I can't get nobody on the label."

322
00:21:42.607 --> 00:21:47.362
And he said. "Well. do you know anybody
you could introduce me to at Motown?"

323
00:21:48.447 --> 00:21:51.280
I was so excited about them.

324
00:21:51.367 --> 00:21:53.835
I told Bobby Taylor that Thursday
about them.

325
00:21:53.927 --> 00:21:55.326
He said. "Okay. I'll look at 'em."

326
00:21:55.447 --> 00:21:58.564
I met them in 1968. at the Regal Theater.

327
00:21:58.927 --> 00:22:00.804
I was headlining the show.

328
00:22:00.887 --> 00:22:01.876
They were the opening act.

329
00:22:01.967 --> 00:22:05.357
and I was introduced to them
by the promoter.

330
00:22:05.447 --> 00:22:09.156
Berry Gordy. President of Motown.
gave him permission

331
00:22:09.247 --> 00:22:14.526
to produce any act that he wanted
and they would listen to it.

332
00:22:15.167 --> 00:22:18.762
He. at that time. had a group
called Bobby Taylor and the Vancouvers.

333
00:22:18.847 --> 00:22:21.919
They had records on the radio
that were going really well and stuff.

334
00:22:29.007 --> 00:22:33.876
I liked the way he sang. 'cause he was
a star vocalist in his own right.

335
00:22:40.167 --> 00:22:44.080
He knew how to do it. when to do it.
why to do it. and why not to do it.

336
00:22:44.527 --> 00:22:47.041
I saw this little kid spinning and stuff.
I said. "Dang.

337
00:22:47.367 --> 00:22:51.360
"Send him upstairs when they finish.
I want to talk to this kid."

338
00:22:52.287 --> 00:22:55.006
Never thought
about recording him at that time.

339
00:22:55.127 --> 00:22:57.880
I said. "This little guy.
I wanna see what's happening."

340
00:22:58.687 --> 00:23:05.081
He was a kid that would worry you. bug you.
until you had to do something with him.

341
00:23:06.047 --> 00:23:09.437
Instead of him going back
to Gary. Indiana. from Chicago

342
00:23:09.527 --> 00:23:14.317
every night. he'd go and ask Joseph
if he could stay with me.

343
00:23:14.807 --> 00:23:17.367
and spend a night at the hotel with me.

344
00:23:17.447 --> 00:23:20.519
So he stayed in my face for 10 straight days.

345
00:23:20.847 --> 00:23:23.156
from the time
that we woke up in the morning.

346
00:23:23.247 --> 00:23:25.556
and I'd take and feed this kid.

347
00:23:25.647 --> 00:23:30.402
It was pure. This kid wanted what he got.

348
00:23:31.127 --> 00:23:33.561
He was a workaholic.

349
00:23:33.767 --> 00:23:35.678
Bobby Taylor worked hard.

350
00:23:35.767 --> 00:23:38.520
I mean. I can't say it enough.
I want people to know.

351
00:23:38.887 --> 00:23:42.596
He worked harder on them
than he did with the Vancouvers.

352
00:23:42.687 --> 00:23:44.962
My motivation was Michael.

353
00:23:45.927 --> 00:23:51.604
I just figured this kid here.
he's an adult in kid's clothing.

354
00:23:52.687 --> 00:23:54.040
That was my only motivation.

355
00:23:54.167 --> 00:23:58.001
Everybody around here knew
that Michael Jackson was "it."

356
00:23:59.207 --> 00:24:01.675
The world just didn't know it.

357
00:24:01.847 --> 00:24:03.075
Bobby was pushing.

358
00:24:03.167 --> 00:24:04.600
When I say he was pushing.

359
00:24:04.687 --> 00:24:09.124
the next time I seen Bobby
or I seen the group.

360
00:24:09.207 --> 00:24:12.404
he had called me and said
he's working at the Apollo.

361
00:24:12.927 --> 00:24:16.966
And come over to the Apollo.
he got a surprise for me.

362
00:24:17.287 --> 00:24:20.882
And when I went to the Apollo.
the Jackson 5 was on the bill.

363
00:24:21.047 --> 00:24:23.117
Apollo Theater
Harlem. New York City

364
00:24:23.207 --> 00:24:26.597
The Apollo was known
as the greatest R&B showroom in the world.

365
00:24:26.687 --> 00:24:28.803
because many albums
had been made from there.

366
00:24:28.887 --> 00:24:31.447
James Brown. Live at the Apollo.

367
00:24:31.527 --> 00:24:33.802
Jackie Wilson played the Apollo.

368
00:24:33.887 --> 00:24:36.242
Gladys Knight and the Pips
played the Apollo.

369
00:24:36.327 --> 00:24:38.363
Smokey Robinson and the Miracles.

370
00:24:38.687 --> 00:24:41.804
Everybody who played the Apollo was a star.

371
00:24:41.887 --> 00:24:45.641
And everybody
who was underneath them on a bill

372
00:24:45.727 --> 00:24:48.400
was trying to gain that national fame.

373
00:24:48.607 --> 00:24:53.158
And if you make it there.
you're assured of stardom

374
00:24:53.247 --> 00:24:57.445
because people knew
that you've got something very special.

375
00:24:57.527 --> 00:24:58.721
It was a very tough audience.

376
00:24:58.807 --> 00:25:02.277
And if they did not like you.
and you were not a good live act.

377
00:25:02.487 --> 00:25:06.446
even though you may have a hit record.
they'd boo you off the stage.

378
00:25:07.287 --> 00:25:09.801
The Jackson 5 tore that place up.

379
00:25:09.887 --> 00:25:14.199
I mean. I've never seen an act
that nobody never heard of.

380
00:25:14.287 --> 00:25:15.766
didn't have a record.

381
00:25:15.847 --> 00:25:18.964
and. I mean.
the people kept hollering. "Jackson 5!"

382
00:25:19.047 --> 00:25:24.246
On the same show was the 5 Stairsteps.
and they were young kids. too.

383
00:25:24.407 --> 00:25:28.116
or they were about the same age
as the Jackson 5.

384
00:25:28.487 --> 00:25:30.762
And they were complaining.

385
00:25:30.967 --> 00:25:34.084
they wanted to get the Jackson 5
off of the show

386
00:25:34.167 --> 00:25:37.796
because every time they went on.
people just hollered.

387
00:25:37.887 --> 00:25:40.640
"Jackson 5! Jackson 5! Jackson 5!"

388
00:25:41.567 --> 00:25:44.240
And I said.
"Wow! I ain't never seen nothing like this."

389
00:25:48.247 --> 00:25:49.236
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

390
00:25:49.327 --> 00:25:52.876
My very first time that I saw Michael Jackson
was at the Apollo Theater in New York.

391
00:25:59.927 --> 00:26:04.000
He and his family were a self-contained act.
which was very unusual.

392
00:26:04.367 --> 00:26:07.598
And yet there was a guitarist in the group
and a bassist in the group.

393
00:26:07.687 --> 00:26:09.643
and keyboard and drums.

394
00:26:16.647 --> 00:26:18.080
They'd won a contest.

395
00:26:18.167 --> 00:26:21.443
They'd won
at the Apollo Theater Amateur Night.

396
00:26:21.527 --> 00:26:25.725
and their prize was to open the show
for the great James Brown.

397
00:26:25.807 --> 00:26:28.446
Well. he broke out into this James Brown.
I Got the Feelin'.

398
00:26:28.527 --> 00:26:31.963
and doing his little toes and dancing
and looking like James.

399
00:26:32.047 --> 00:26:33.685
if James were a wind-up toy.

400
00:26:33.967 --> 00:26:35.764
And it was amazing.

401
00:26:35.967 --> 00:26:37.002
Rebbie Jackson
MICHAEL'S SISTER

402
00:26:37.087 --> 00:26:39.681
He would perform and do the moves
and routine that everyone else was doing.

403
00:26:39.807 --> 00:26:43.561
He used to do Fred Astaire
and James Cagney.

404
00:26:43.687 --> 00:26:47.202
Then all of a sudden. he would add
a little bit of something in there. different.

405
00:26:47.287 --> 00:26:49.642
And that was him feeling what he was doing.

406
00:26:50.407 --> 00:26:53.319
He excited me. I saw all of this in him.

407
00:26:53.407 --> 00:26:55.637
I saw things that he could do that I couldn't.

408
00:26:56.767 --> 00:26:59.406
He had the makings of a great singer.

409
00:26:59.567 --> 00:27:02.798
Michael had universal appeal
back when he was real young.

410
00:27:02.887 --> 00:27:06.118
I mean. we weren't really into marketing
or anything like that.

411
00:27:06.207 --> 00:27:07.879
but it was already there.

412
00:27:07.967 --> 00:27:10.640
I think the word for it.
the phraseology. would be.

413
00:27:10.727 --> 00:27:15.084
"A diamond in the rough."
without very many edges to buff off.

414
00:27:19.847 --> 00:27:21.599
With the rest of the brothers. now.

415
00:27:21.967 --> 00:27:23.400
Jermaine stuttered.

416
00:27:23.687 --> 00:27:26.076
And he always thought
that if he stuttered when he talked.

417
00:27:26.167 --> 00:27:27.395
that he would do it when he sang.

418
00:27:28.207 --> 00:27:30.960
So I had to push Jermaine more than I had
to push anyone else.

419
00:27:31.167 --> 00:27:35.126
And that's all I used.
Jermaine. Michael and Jackie.

420
00:27:35.487 --> 00:27:37.921
I did not use Marlon. did not use Tito.

421
00:27:38.167 --> 00:27:40.078
They couldn't sing. right?

422
00:27:40.167 --> 00:27:42.635
And I told them. "Learn. Listen and learn."

423
00:27:42.847 --> 00:27:45.725
The complete group
was not just those five boys.

424
00:27:46.167 --> 00:27:48.761
The complete group
had two other ones with them.

425
00:27:48.967 --> 00:27:50.878
one was Johnny Jackson. the drummer.

426
00:27:50.967 --> 00:27:53.435
one was Ronnie Rancifer. the pianist.

427
00:27:53.967 --> 00:27:56.879
which made the music for the group.

428
00:27:56.967 --> 00:27:59.401
Without them.
there wouldn't have been this Jackson 5.

429
00:28:01.487 --> 00:28:04.445
Every producer
has their own method to the madness.

430
00:28:04.527 --> 00:28:06.518
and Bobby's was pretty cool.

431
00:28:06.607 --> 00:28:09.326
He had the old-school roughness on that.
you know.

432
00:28:09.407 --> 00:28:11.363
You have to have
a certain kind of roughness.

433
00:28:11.447 --> 00:28:12.800
a certain kind of discipline.

434
00:28:12.887 --> 00:28:17.483
He felt Michael had something so special.
and he told that to him.

435
00:28:18.647 --> 00:28:19.682
But he said.

436
00:28:19.767 --> 00:28:24.522
"Do not think
just me telling you makes it happen.

437
00:28:25.287 --> 00:28:27.164
"It does not.

438
00:28:27.247 --> 00:28:32.082
"You've gotta work and continue to work
for what you achieve.

439
00:28:32.167 --> 00:28:33.839
"It will never be easy."

440
00:28:34.207 --> 00:28:37.199
He wasn't always patient.

441
00:28:37.287 --> 00:28:40.518
He wasn't always saying things
that you wanna hear.

442
00:28:40.607 --> 00:28:42.199
or saying it right.

443
00:28:42.287 --> 00:28:47.645
But what he said and what he was doing
was just trying to make them stars.

444
00:28:48.167 --> 00:28:52.479
Our last day at the Regal Theater

445
00:28:52.567 --> 00:28:54.762
is when I went to Joe. I said.

446
00:28:54.847 --> 00:28:57.998
"Say now. why don't you let me
put these kids at Motown?"

447
00:29:00.567 --> 00:29:03.957
And Joe said those words to me.
"Man. I thought you'd never ask."

448
00:29:08.927 --> 00:29:09.916
We were in New York City.

449
00:29:10.007 --> 00:29:10.996
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

450
00:29:11.087 --> 00:29:14.443
And we had just finished
performing with James Brown.

451
00:29:14.527 --> 00:29:16.119
We were opening up for him.

452
00:29:17.247 --> 00:29:19.920
Bobby Taylor had been begging Berry
to check us out.

453
00:29:20.447 --> 00:29:21.596
Berry Gordy - FOUNDER.
MOTOWN RECORD CORPORATION

454
00:29:21.687 --> 00:29:24.360
And he wouldn't do it
because he had another kid on his label.

455
00:29:24.927 --> 00:29:29.364
And he was catching a lot of flak
from the state

456
00:29:29.447 --> 00:29:32.962
about working this kid who's underage.

457
00:29:33.047 --> 00:29:37.484
Berry would say. "I never wanna have
anything to do with kids in this business.

458
00:29:37.567 --> 00:29:38.556
"It's too much problems.

459
00:29:38.647 --> 00:29:42.322
"I can't even handle one.
What am I gonna do with five?"

460
00:29:42.407 --> 00:29:44.523
And the one kid was little Stevie Wonder.

461
00:29:46.687 --> 00:29:49.121
I drove Michael. Marlon.

462
00:29:50.327 --> 00:29:53.205
Tommy Chong. who was in my band.
from Cheech and Chong.

463
00:29:53.287 --> 00:29:55.596
from Chicago to Detroit.

464
00:29:55.687 --> 00:29:58.201
I take Michael directly to Motown.

465
00:29:58.647 --> 00:30:01.878
So I said. "Berry. I've got these kids here

466
00:30:01.967 --> 00:30:04.765
"and they're number one coming
out of the block."

467
00:30:05.007 --> 00:30:07.282
I said. "The lead singer's eight.

468
00:30:07.847 --> 00:30:09.963
"He can out-dance anybody you ever saw.

469
00:30:10.087 --> 00:30:11.566
"Jackie Wilson. James Brown.

470
00:30:11.647 --> 00:30:16.562
"If you close your eyes and listen to him
after I finish teaching him.

471
00:30:16.647 --> 00:30:18.239
"the best singer you ever heard in your life."

472
00:30:18.327 --> 00:30:24.277
It was not easy to get a children's group
signed to Motown.

473
00:30:24.767 --> 00:30:28.885
And Bobby Taylor knew
that when he called Berry

474
00:30:29.207 --> 00:30:32.882
and said. "I've got something so special.
you gotta see it."

475
00:30:34.127 --> 00:30:36.436
that Berry would jump once he did.

476
00:30:36.647 --> 00:30:41.084
Because he would not have taken them
to Berry to waste his time.

477
00:30:42.407 --> 00:30:48.482
The next morning. Berry Gordy
called me from Los Angeles. and he says.

478
00:30:48.567 --> 00:30:50.523
"I want you to bring them out here."

479
00:30:52.727 --> 00:30:54.160
That's how they got to Motown.

480
00:31:00.607 --> 00:31:02.359
Going to California.
the happiest day of my life.

481
00:31:02.447 --> 00:31:03.436
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

482
00:31:06.087 --> 00:31:09.921
Joseph had promised me that one day
we would go to California.

483
00:31:11.167 --> 00:31:13.681
I'd tell him. "No."
I said. "Your promise came true.

484
00:31:13.767 --> 00:31:16.406
"but you didn't bring me there.
the children did."

485
00:31:20.487 --> 00:31:23.160
Berry Gordy was having a party
for Diana Ross.

486
00:31:23.247 --> 00:31:24.726
It was her birthday.

487
00:31:24.807 --> 00:31:28.277
So he asked us to perform
at this party for Diana.

488
00:31:28.927 --> 00:31:30.599
and of course we did.

489
00:31:30.687 --> 00:31:35.397
And at that party was. like. the Temptations.
Smokey. the Vandellas.

490
00:31:35.487 --> 00:31:38.604
the Supremes. Four Tops.

491
00:31:38.687 --> 00:31:41.679
And here we are performing
their songs to them.

492
00:31:41.767 --> 00:31:43.041
So we was quite nervous.

493
00:31:43.887 --> 00:31:44.922
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

494
00:31:45.007 --> 00:31:48.602
I first met Michael. he was.
I think he was 10 years old.

495
00:31:48.727 --> 00:31:50.683
He was flown out with his brothers

496
00:31:50.767 --> 00:31:53.201
to sing for Berry Gordy. Jr.

497
00:31:53.887 --> 00:31:57.277
Berry had invited a bunch of people
up to his home.

498
00:31:57.367 --> 00:32:01.599
This little bitty thing came in
and he sat down next to me

499
00:32:02.407 --> 00:32:04.967
and he looked at me and he says.
"And who are you?"

500
00:32:05.047 --> 00:32:07.686
I said. "I'm Dionne Warwick. Who are you?"

501
00:32:08.327 --> 00:32:09.885
"I'm Michael Jackson."

502
00:32:09.967 --> 00:32:14.165
I said. "Nice to know you. Michael Jackson.
And what do you do. Michael Jackson?"

503
00:32:14.687 --> 00:32:16.882
He says. "Oh. I sing."

504
00:32:17.687 --> 00:32:21.077
I said. "You sing? Can you sing?"

505
00:32:21.527 --> 00:32:23.677
He said. "Yes. I can sing."

506
00:32:24.207 --> 00:32:27.643
I mean. little feisty. beautiful young boy.

507
00:32:27.727 --> 00:32:30.799
I said. "Well. that's what we're here for.
We're gonna see if you can sing."

508
00:32:38.527 --> 00:32:41.360
Watching them perform was excitement.

509
00:32:41.447 --> 00:32:42.436
Brenda Holloway
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

510
00:32:42.527 --> 00:32:44.597
Everyone in the group was an individual.

511
00:32:47.567 --> 00:32:50.559
And I feel that every one of them
could have gone on their own.

512
00:32:50.647 --> 00:32:52.126
But Michael was the star.

513
00:32:58.927 --> 00:33:03.125
They came in
and they sang a few songs.

514
00:33:03.207 --> 00:33:05.198
They sang a couple songs
by James Brown. you know.

515
00:33:05.287 --> 00:33:06.276
Smokey Robinson
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

516
00:33:06.367 --> 00:33:11.680
and Michael did the James Brown dances.
and he really did them.

517
00:33:11.767 --> 00:33:15.396
He's 10 years old and he was dancing
like he was about 30.

518
00:33:15.487 --> 00:33:20.003
How in the world could this little boy.
and he was a kid.

519
00:33:20.087 --> 00:33:21.361
be so talented?

520
00:33:21.487 --> 00:33:23.717
That's what everybody went away
talking about.

521
00:33:28.527 --> 00:33:31.758
I think all of us
Motown artists were astonished

522
00:33:31.847 --> 00:33:32.836
Kim Weston
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

523
00:33:32.927 --> 00:33:36.602
because here's a kid that. you know.
seemed to have no fear.

524
00:33:36.687 --> 00:33:42.557
You know. when the music hit. he was ready.
you know. or ready before the music hit.

525
00:33:42.887 --> 00:33:44.684
He said.
"I want you to know something. too."

526
00:33:44.767 --> 00:33:45.995
I said. "What's that?"

527
00:33:46.087 --> 00:33:49.318
"You sang a song about my name. Michael."

528
00:33:50.407 --> 00:33:53.524
I said. "Yeah.
You think that song was for you?"

529
00:33:55.047 --> 00:33:56.765
He said. "Wasn't it?"

530
00:33:58.967 --> 00:34:02.437
He was an adorable child.
It was a wonderful meeting.

531
00:34:03.127 --> 00:34:05.277
They loved it. They enjoyed it.

532
00:34:05.647 --> 00:34:07.319
That was our audition.

533
00:34:08.527 --> 00:34:11.564
So I'm very proud of that moment in our life.

534
00:34:16.007 --> 00:34:17.884
There was another world about to open

535
00:34:17.967 --> 00:34:18.956
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

536
00:34:19.047 --> 00:34:21.197
and he was ready to delve into it.

537
00:34:21.407 --> 00:34:22.635
Marvin Gaye

538
00:34:22.727 --> 00:34:23.796
Junior Walker

539
00:34:23.887 --> 00:34:25.525
When you went to Motown. it was...
Everyone was there.

540
00:34:25.607 --> 00:34:26.960
The Isley Brothers

541
00:34:27.047 --> 00:34:28.036
Kim Weston

542
00:34:28.127 --> 00:34:29.196
Edwin Starr

543
00:34:29.287 --> 00:34:30.276
Jimmy Ruffin

544
00:34:30.367 --> 00:34:33.757
It was like Disneyland. You saw Smokey.
you saw Mary. you saw Diana Ross.

545
00:34:33.847 --> 00:34:37.601
But everybody was trying
to perfect their artistry.

546
00:34:37.687 --> 00:34:39.962
The feeling at Motown was it was a family.
a musical family.

547
00:34:40.047 --> 00:34:41.241
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford

548
00:34:41.327 --> 00:34:42.442
SINGERS I SONGWRITERS.
'ASHFORD & SIMPSON'

549
00:34:42.527 --> 00:34:46.076
And we all were a part of excellence
and greatness. musical greatness.

550
00:34:46.167 --> 00:34:49.125
And we so were fans of each other's work.

551
00:34:49.207 --> 00:34:52.324
so that when we saw each other.
it was just instant love.

552
00:34:52.407 --> 00:34:56.036
We got. "We knew what you were doing.
I heard what you're working on."

553
00:34:56.127 --> 00:34:58.641
And it just... We kept pushing each other.

554
00:34:58.847 --> 00:35:00.917
When you start working
with the best in the business

555
00:35:01.007 --> 00:35:02.360
Russell Thompkins. Jr.
LEAD SINGER. 'THE STYLISTICS'

556
00:35:02.447 --> 00:35:04.085
that are teaching you how to dance.
how to play this

557
00:35:04.167 --> 00:35:07.364
and teaching you how to sing this.
putting you at the piano.

558
00:35:07.447 --> 00:35:11.725
vocal coaches. dancing coaches.
people who teach you how to talk.

559
00:35:11.807 --> 00:35:14.799
When you work with that from the time
that you're a young man.

560
00:35:14.967 --> 00:35:17.640
you grow up with so much influence.

561
00:35:17.807 --> 00:35:20.321
So it wasn't just the fact
that Michael Jackson

562
00:35:20.407 --> 00:35:24.116
was born with so much great talent.
He always had it around him.

563
00:35:29.207 --> 00:35:31.163
Michael Jackson studied all the artists.
all the great artists.

564
00:35:31.247 --> 00:35:32.236
Jimmy Ruffin
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

565
00:35:34.607 --> 00:35:37.167
He studied me. he studied Marvin Gaye.
he studied Stevie Wonder.

566
00:35:37.247 --> 00:35:38.521
He studied everybody.

567
00:35:38.607 --> 00:35:43.078
We were the best in the country at the time.

568
00:35:48.247 --> 00:35:51.239
The first time I saw them perform
was in San Francisco

569
00:35:51.327 --> 00:35:53.079
and I was like. "Wow."

570
00:35:53.167 --> 00:35:55.397
It was like. "There's nobody that good."

571
00:36:00.847 --> 00:36:03.964
Berry Gordy was like.
"Keep your cards close to your chest.

572
00:36:04.407 --> 00:36:06.477
"Don't let people know what you're thinking.

573
00:36:07.167 --> 00:36:10.318
"Don't let the artists know
how much people like 'em."

574
00:36:10.847 --> 00:36:12.519
He was a shrewd guy.

575
00:36:15.207 --> 00:36:19.962
Berry looked after every aspect
of an artist's career.

576
00:36:20.047 --> 00:36:24.245
Now. some may complain today
that they didn't get paid enough royalties

577
00:36:24.327 --> 00:36:27.956
and they never received
a lot of their publishing.

578
00:36:28.047 --> 00:36:29.526
But I'll tell you something.

579
00:36:30.087 --> 00:36:33.602
Berry Gordy made these artists.

580
00:36:34.007 --> 00:36:35.725
Everybody. I think.
had different relationships with Berry.

581
00:36:35.807 --> 00:36:36.796
Abdul 'Duke' Fakir
ARTIST. 'THE FOUR TOPS'

582
00:36:36.887 --> 00:36:39.640
We had a great relationship with Berry
and we still do.

583
00:36:39.727 --> 00:36:43.686
He gave us... He promised us things
that he made come true.

584
00:36:43.767 --> 00:36:48.443
that he couldn't put in the contract.
But he promised them and kept his word.

585
00:36:48.527 --> 00:36:54.477
What he saw in the Jackson 5
was a children's group that could transcend

586
00:36:54.967 --> 00:36:58.880
every age group.
And he nurtured their talents.

587
00:36:59.527 --> 00:37:01.324
He knew he had something special.

588
00:37:01.727 --> 00:37:04.639
I made him sit in while I was doing the music

589
00:37:04.727 --> 00:37:05.716
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY I MOTOWN RECORDS

590
00:37:06.327 --> 00:37:08.045
that they had to work with.

591
00:37:08.367 --> 00:37:12.519
They were with me 20 hours a day.

592
00:37:12.607 --> 00:37:15.405
Being attentive. if I saw somebody sleeping.

593
00:37:15.487 --> 00:37:17.557
then I would send them back to the house

594
00:37:17.647 --> 00:37:19.717
and tell them.
"I don't wanna see you for a week."

595
00:37:19.807 --> 00:37:22.196
They worked hard. they really worked hard.

596
00:37:23.687 --> 00:37:28.397
Michael now would stay
over at Diana Ross's house and rehearse.

597
00:37:28.607 --> 00:37:31.246
He really liked Diana Ross
and she liked him.

598
00:37:31.647 --> 00:37:33.922
Diana Ross was
showing him off.

599
00:37:34.047 --> 00:37:36.925
She just like...
She was the one that discovered him

600
00:37:37.007 --> 00:37:41.842
and later on I found out that Bobby Taylor
actually discovered him.

601
00:37:43.487 --> 00:37:44.681
I think we were just kids.

602
00:37:44.767 --> 00:37:48.646
We didn't realise
all the great accomplishments

603
00:37:48.727 --> 00:37:50.399
that we had achieved.

604
00:37:50.487 --> 00:37:55.607
Seeing Hollywood and playing
with Diana Ross. I mean. we were in heaven.

605
00:37:55.687 --> 00:37:59.202
Just those things alone was priceless to us.

606
00:37:59.327 --> 00:38:01.761
Michael told me when he came to LA.

607
00:38:01.847 --> 00:38:04.600
it was like his whole world had changed.

608
00:38:05.087 --> 00:38:10.207
He could buy as much candy as he wanted
because nobody would say no to him.

609
00:38:16.927 --> 00:38:19.441
Michael and I went to see the Four Tops.

610
00:38:19.527 --> 00:38:25.045
it was around 1971 or '72.

611
00:38:29.047 --> 00:38:31.083
Michael and David just came
to the dressing room

612
00:38:31.167 --> 00:38:33.476
and in the dressing room
was also Stevie Wonder.

613
00:38:34.207 --> 00:38:38.041
I said to Levi Stubbs.
"You're brilliant. I love your voice."

614
00:38:38.127 --> 00:38:41.881
And Michael looked at him and said.
"I learned everything from you."

615
00:38:41.967 --> 00:38:44.162
And he was cut off. Stevie said. "What?"

616
00:38:44.367 --> 00:38:47.120
And he grabbed Michael
and flung him up against the wall...

617
00:38:47.207 --> 00:38:49.641
And said.
"You learned everything from who?"

618
00:38:49.727 --> 00:38:51.718
And he goes. "You. Stevie. you."

619
00:38:51.847 --> 00:38:54.645
It was so funny. It was so funny.

620
00:38:55.127 --> 00:38:56.958
Levi and I. we never forgot that.

621
00:38:58.807 --> 00:39:01.958
Bobby Taylor and I would take
Michael to the golf course with us.

622
00:39:02.047 --> 00:39:05.198
He had never even picked up
a golf club in his life.

623
00:39:05.287 --> 00:39:07.847
Yet. he was our greatest golf critic.

624
00:39:08.247 --> 00:39:10.636
"Well. Smokey. you know.
you hit your ball over in the woods

625
00:39:10.727 --> 00:39:13.764
"because you didn't have your foot
standing right here..."

626
00:39:14.327 --> 00:39:20.118
"Bobby. see. your club was not. you know..."
He's gonna tell us why we had a bad shot.

627
00:39:20.487 --> 00:39:23.081
But it was fun. He was a great. fun kid.

628
00:39:26.367 --> 00:39:28.961
The first time I heard
I Want You Back in the studio.

629
00:39:29.047 --> 00:39:33.245
I noticed a different kind of brightness
to the movement.

630
00:39:33.327 --> 00:39:34.476
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST. 'JACKSON 5' 1967-77

631
00:39:34.567 --> 00:39:36.842
other than normal Motown brightness.

632
00:39:37.487 --> 00:39:39.478
It was going in a different direction.

633
00:39:39.567 --> 00:39:43.037
which was good
because Motown's sound was diversified.

634
00:39:43.247 --> 00:39:47.160
When you listened to I Want You Back.
you knew Berry had a knack to get

635
00:39:47.247 --> 00:39:51.035
the best commercial record out of these kids

636
00:39:51.127 --> 00:39:53.322
and make them a worldwide success.

637
00:40:00.727 --> 00:40:06.040
When my sister and my mom first heard
our first hit record. I Want You Back.

638
00:40:06.127 --> 00:40:09.119
my father had sent it over.
they didn't care for it.

639
00:40:09.327 --> 00:40:10.965
I didn't like it at all.

640
00:40:11.047 --> 00:40:13.515
Because the songs that the children sang

641
00:40:13.607 --> 00:40:17.122
was more like the. I should say. soul music.

642
00:40:17.767 --> 00:40:20.565
And to me. I Want You Back
didn't sound that way.

643
00:40:21.167 --> 00:40:24.682
All the songs that was out then
sound so different.

644
00:40:24.767 --> 00:40:27.327
so I guess Berry wanted
to bring out a different style.

645
00:40:27.407 --> 00:40:31.286
Little did they know it was a very big song.
number one.

646
00:40:41.647 --> 00:40:43.683
It was just an unbelievable track.

647
00:40:43.767 --> 00:40:47.237
It just came out of the radio like lightning.

648
00:40:47.327 --> 00:40:51.639
Oh. them Jackson 5. that is a kickin' group.

649
00:40:51.727 --> 00:40:56.005
"Wow. that's them?"
And I had to get used to the song

650
00:40:56.447 --> 00:40:59.041
because even though it was a very big hit.

651
00:41:00.767 --> 00:41:03.884
your brothers singing on a record.
on vinyl. and you hearing it

652
00:41:03.967 --> 00:41:05.400
is something totally different.

653
00:41:05.967 --> 00:41:06.956
We just don't have songs
that come and go.

654
00:41:07.047 --> 00:41:09.242
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

655
00:41:09.327 --> 00:41:10.999
we have songs that'll be around all the time.

656
00:41:11.087 --> 00:41:13.681
Like. you'll hear 'em
on the FM classical stations.

657
00:41:13.767 --> 00:41:16.679
by the Philharmonic Orchestra.
things like that.

658
00:41:16.767 --> 00:41:20.840
So it's just not what people call it.
kiddie rock. It's not that.

659
00:41:21.527 --> 00:41:23.483
And a million sellers. a million selling.

660
00:41:23.807 --> 00:41:25.206
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON'S FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

661
00:41:25.287 --> 00:41:28.916
It was difficult to believe
that they were Motown artists.

662
00:41:29.047 --> 00:41:30.878
because they were just kids.

663
00:41:30.967 --> 00:41:34.118
It was as if they had some
kind of stardust rub off on them

664
00:41:34.207 --> 00:41:37.722
because. you know. they were
becoming close to Berry Gordy.

665
00:41:37.807 --> 00:41:40.401
Diana Ross. and to all of my idols.

666
00:41:45.847 --> 00:41:48.725
When I wrote Who's Lovin' You.
I was. you know. in my early 20s.

667
00:41:48.807 --> 00:41:49.796
Smokey Robinson
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

668
00:41:58.807 --> 00:42:03.119
But at least. at that point.
I had had a chance to experience

669
00:42:03.247 --> 00:42:05.124
some life and some love.

670
00:42:05.207 --> 00:42:07.926
I was married. I got married when I was 19.

671
00:42:08.847 --> 00:42:12.442
The subject matter
of the song is like a person

672
00:42:12.527 --> 00:42:16.315
who has somebody who really loves them.

673
00:42:16.807 --> 00:42:18.923
And yet they don't appreciate it.
They do the person wrong.

674
00:42:19.207 --> 00:42:21.277
The first time I heard Smokey's
Who's Lovin' You.

675
00:42:21.367 --> 00:42:23.881
my assistant was playing it
and it's one of those.

676
00:42:24.007 --> 00:42:30.719
oh. party. red-light. basement-type.
you know. up on it.

677
00:42:32.927 --> 00:42:34.758
But when Michael got ahold to it.

678
00:42:34.847 --> 00:42:38.078
and Bobby Taylor infused him up
with that funk.

679
00:42:38.167 --> 00:42:42.399
man. Michael put that soul
in that song so deep. it was soulful.

680
00:42:59.527 --> 00:43:02.997
How could he possibly know
what that song meant?

681
00:43:03.167 --> 00:43:04.805
He sang it like he had written it.

682
00:43:07.367 --> 00:43:10.837
I sing Who's Lovin' You. or part of it.
in my live concerts

683
00:43:11.487 --> 00:43:14.763
and many times. young people have
come up to me after the concert and said.

684
00:43:14.847 --> 00:43:17.077
"Oh. I didn't know
you sang Michael Jackson's song."

685
00:43:24.247 --> 00:43:29.002
A kid. 11 years old. singing that song
with that much emotion? It was incredible.

686
00:43:29.207 --> 00:43:30.242
Unbelievable.

687
00:43:44.087 --> 00:43:46.442
He seemed as if he was an old soul.

688
00:43:46.887 --> 00:43:50.118
that he could take a song like
Who's Lovin' You

689
00:43:50.247 --> 00:43:53.922
and he could actually interpret those lyrics

690
00:43:54.007 --> 00:43:55.884
in a way that made you believe

691
00:43:55.967 --> 00:43:59.437
that he had those experiences.
when actually he was 10 years old.

692
00:43:59.807 --> 00:44:03.163
If you didn't know he was a kid.
you'd have thought he was an old man.

693
00:44:04.527 --> 00:44:06.324
But he was singing it from his heart.

694
00:44:06.407 --> 00:44:08.602
You know. Michael's life
was kind of paradoxical to me.

695
00:44:08.687 --> 00:44:12.157
because when he was a child. he was a man.

696
00:44:12.607 --> 00:44:15.280
So when he was a man. he got the chance
to be a child and he took it.

697
00:44:26.727 --> 00:44:32.085
He had a way of interpreting a lyric.
even as a very young boy.

698
00:44:32.287 --> 00:44:34.721
that made you believe the song.

699
00:44:47.727 --> 00:44:49.604
He knew how to perform.

700
00:44:49.967 --> 00:44:52.800
This was. I think. something
that Berry Gordy really liked about Michael

701
00:44:52.887 --> 00:44:55.447
because. not only was he a great vocal talent.

702
00:44:55.527 --> 00:44:56.880
but he was a great performer.

703
00:44:56.967 --> 00:44:59.162
Watching him. as a kid.
be so comfortable performing

704
00:44:59.247 --> 00:45:00.282
Peabo Bryson
SINGER

705
00:45:00.367 --> 00:45:05.282
probably helped me
become a better performer. actually.

706
00:45:05.567 --> 00:45:07.444
His voice was nearly
as high as Stevie Wonder's.

707
00:45:07.527 --> 00:45:08.562
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

708
00:45:08.647 --> 00:45:10.558
I met Stevie when he was eight years old

709
00:45:10.687 --> 00:45:16.876
and I said. "Here's another little youngster
who's far beyond his age. talent-wise.

710
00:45:16.967 --> 00:45:21.119
"but able to sing adult songs
in perfect-pitched voices.

711
00:45:21.207 --> 00:45:23.437
"real high voices that hadn't changed yet."

712
00:45:31.887 --> 00:45:34.037
His voice and his expressions and his...

713
00:45:34.127 --> 00:45:35.116
Weldon Arthur McDougal III

714
00:45:35.207 --> 00:45:36.196
A & R EXECUTIVE.
MOTOWN RECORDS 1969-80

715
00:45:36.287 --> 00:45:39.757
...charisma start taking these songs over.

716
00:45:40.647 --> 00:45:44.401
Like. if Smokey felt like he did his song

717
00:45:44.487 --> 00:45:47.047
and more people like the way Michael
did it than him.

718
00:45:47.127 --> 00:45:49.846
that's because he did that with all
of his songs at that time.

719
00:45:55.327 --> 00:46:00.845
No matter who it was. the O'Jays. the Dells.
the Whispers or the Beatles.

720
00:46:01.287 --> 00:46:02.959
we wanted to be the best.

721
00:46:03.087 --> 00:46:06.318
And that's what we were striving for.

722
00:46:08.287 --> 00:46:14.681
Berry Gordy did not like the stuff
that Bobby Taylor was recording on them.

723
00:46:14.807 --> 00:46:20.837
I wanted to do the boys a certain way.
but he wanted me to do 'em his way.

724
00:46:22.087 --> 00:46:25.682
And I says. "I can't do 'em the way
you want me to do 'em.

725
00:46:25.767 --> 00:46:27.439
"I must have my own head."

726
00:46:27.527 --> 00:46:29.245
So he says.
"Okay. well. go on back to Detroit."

727
00:46:29.567 --> 00:46:31.046
Then he took over.

728
00:46:31.127 --> 00:46:35.996
Berry Gordy. in turn.
put his crew together.

729
00:46:36.447 --> 00:46:40.725
The Corporation was established
to bring fresh new material

730
00:46:41.127 --> 00:46:42.719
to the Jackson 5.

731
00:46:42.807 --> 00:46:44.320
Youthful material.

732
00:46:44.607 --> 00:46:50.045
I think he probably felt
that Bobby Taylor would

733
00:46:51.327 --> 00:46:56.162
give them more adult material
and forget that they were children.

734
00:46:56.247 --> 00:46:59.876
He saw gazillions. right?

735
00:47:00.247 --> 00:47:01.396
Then he took over.

736
00:47:01.487 --> 00:47:05.924
Bobby Taylor did never get the recognition
he should have gotten

737
00:47:06.527 --> 00:47:08.324
for working with them.

738
00:47:09.567 --> 00:47:11.717
from the group or the public.

739
00:47:13.887 --> 00:47:18.915
Bobby Taylor produced 10 songs on the
album: 'Diana Ross Presents The Jackson 5'

740
00:47:20.647 --> 00:47:25.846
During 1969-70 the Jackson 5
released 4 number one singles in a row.

741
00:47:32.447 --> 00:47:34.085
The Corporation. is
what they called themselves.

742
00:47:34.167 --> 00:47:38.683
they topped themselves
with those early songs by the Jackson 5.

743
00:47:38.767 --> 00:47:40.200
they were absolutely incredible.

744
00:47:40.287 --> 00:47:42.164
Absolutely incredible.

745
00:47:42.407 --> 00:47:46.082
When my boys had
five gold records in a row.

746
00:47:48.127 --> 00:47:52.166
I was very proud of them because I know
it was something that they wanted

747
00:47:52.327 --> 00:47:55.000
and it was their dream.

748
00:47:55.087 --> 00:47:58.079
And they were happy and I was happy.

749
00:47:58.207 --> 00:48:00.198
The whole family was happy about that.

750
00:48:04.767 --> 00:48:06.997
We did a show once for Jesse Jackson.

751
00:48:07.087 --> 00:48:08.122
Dennis Edwards
LEAD SINGER. 'THE TEMPTATIONS'

752
00:48:08.207 --> 00:48:09.879
You know. Jesse Jackson. he's the activist.

753
00:48:09.967 --> 00:48:13.437
He's got an organisation called PUSH Expo.

754
00:48:13.567 --> 00:48:15.603
He booked the Temptations
and the Jackson 5.

755
00:48:15.687 --> 00:48:17.086
They were just up and coming.

756
00:48:17.167 --> 00:48:22.400
We were superstars at that time
and. oh. man. it was so many people.

757
00:48:24.727 --> 00:48:26.957
When they did that show.

758
00:48:27.527 --> 00:48:29.916
the Temptations got a great response.

759
00:48:32.047 --> 00:48:35.596
When the Jackson 5 came on.
it was phenomenal.

760
00:48:36.047 --> 00:48:38.197
I mean. almost blew the roof off the place.

761
00:48:42.087 --> 00:48:43.679
They couldn't get us to our limos.

762
00:48:43.767 --> 00:48:47.123
They had to back up an armoured car.
a Brink's car.

763
00:48:47.207 --> 00:48:50.119
It's like a moment in history.

764
00:48:50.887 --> 00:48:55.483
That's when they finally made it
with the black R&B public.

765
00:48:55.927 --> 00:48:58.600
They were just ripe for stardom.

766
00:49:01.327 --> 00:49:04.160
On the stage. he was a different guy.

767
00:49:06.887 --> 00:49:11.165
He was really as much of an actor
in so many ways as he was a singer.

768
00:49:11.767 --> 00:49:13.166
A lot of people always come up
to a lot of us and say

769
00:49:13.247 --> 00:49:15.442
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

770
00:49:15.527 --> 00:49:16.516
it's like two different people.

771
00:49:16.607 --> 00:49:18.484
On stage and off stage.

772
00:49:18.567 --> 00:49:23.083
When we was talking. he's shy
and. you know. very soft spoken.

773
00:49:23.567 --> 00:49:25.922
But just when he jumped
on that stage. he's like...

774
00:49:36.047 --> 00:49:38.515
Well. I mean. he was a different person

775
00:49:38.727 --> 00:49:42.197
and I've never seen
that in another artist's life.

776
00:49:42.807 --> 00:49:44.445
He was like two guys.

777
00:49:44.567 --> 00:49:48.242
Anything he felt that he wanted to do.
he would do it on stage.

778
00:50:00.887 --> 00:50:03.196
The moment he came off of the stage.

779
00:50:03.287 --> 00:50:07.838
he was back to the little boy he was
before he went on stage.

780
00:50:14.927 --> 00:50:17.487
When I get on stage. I really.
totally do. That's with a lot of performers.

781
00:50:17.567 --> 00:50:19.762
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

782
00:50:19.847 --> 00:50:20.836
I've learned that about comedians. too.

783
00:50:20.927 --> 00:50:23.316
It's like when I worked with Richard Pryor
in The Wiz.

784
00:50:23.407 --> 00:50:26.240
A lot of people think he's the funniest guy
to be around 24 hours.

785
00:50:26.327 --> 00:50:29.000
That's not true. He's really shy and quiet.

786
00:50:29.327 --> 00:50:30.965
We were all like that. too.

787
00:50:31.047 --> 00:50:35.040
Singing or dancing
in front of. like. one person. can't do it.

788
00:50:35.127 --> 00:50:38.597
But. like. it's 30.000. you feel so free.
so much easier.

789
00:50:38.687 --> 00:50:39.756
It's hard to explain.

790
00:50:47.687 --> 00:50:50.645
What motivates Michael Jackson?

791
00:50:51.487 --> 00:50:53.284
That was an audience.

792
00:50:53.687 --> 00:50:54.802
Think about it.

793
00:50:54.887 --> 00:51:00.120
He's shy. he won't look at you. right?

794
00:51:00.287 --> 00:51:01.402
On stage. what is he?

795
00:51:07.727 --> 00:51:09.240
He owns it.

796
00:51:09.767 --> 00:51:12.122
So if I had people looking at him.

797
00:51:12.207 --> 00:51:15.199
I used to bring five. six girls
every time. right?

798
00:51:15.327 --> 00:51:18.478
And I'd say. "Michael. look at that girl. man.
They think you're cute."

799
00:51:18.567 --> 00:51:21.843
Michael'd say.
"Dang. Bobby. they said that?"

800
00:51:21.927 --> 00:51:25.078
I said. "You better go out there
and sing now. son."

801
00:51:33.967 --> 00:51:36.925
I said. "You go out there
and you mess up now." I said.

802
00:51:37.007 --> 00:51:38.884
"They're gonna tell all the rest of the girls
out there.

803
00:51:38.967 --> 00:51:41.527
"You're gonna be one ugly little boy
everywhere you go."

804
00:51:50.007 --> 00:51:53.044
He used to go out and do one take.

805
00:51:58.007 --> 00:52:02.683
When we were on the road.
Michael would worry you to death.

806
00:52:02.967 --> 00:52:04.605
I hear somebody knocking on my door
and say.

807
00:52:04.687 --> 00:52:09.158
"Hey. man. what's wrong?" "Oh. man.
what you doing? I wanna come in."

808
00:52:09.247 --> 00:52:13.718
So I'd let him in. I'd say. "Man. why don't
you hang out with Jackie and them guys?"

809
00:52:13.807 --> 00:52:16.116
"Hey. man. they got somebody in their room."

810
00:52:18.167 --> 00:52:19.919
I said. "Well. how do you know?"

811
00:52:20.007 --> 00:52:22.680
He said. "'Cause I was listening
to the door for about an hour."

812
00:52:25.967 --> 00:52:28.276
He was like a little boy. I mean. he...

813
00:52:28.407 --> 00:52:29.556
I said. "What were they doing?"

814
00:52:29.647 --> 00:52:31.877
He said. "They were talking.
but they won't let me in."

815
00:52:32.407 --> 00:52:37.925
They were like little kids
and they were very. very happy

816
00:52:38.007 --> 00:52:39.486
and very carefree.

817
00:52:39.607 --> 00:52:42.075
Michael loved being
Michael Jackson at that age.

818
00:52:43.127 --> 00:52:46.119
He loved touring.
he loved recording at Motown.

819
00:52:46.207 --> 00:52:49.756
He loved his fans. he loved performing.

820
00:52:50.127 --> 00:52:54.803
They had dirt bikes
and they used to go on Saturday mornings.

821
00:52:54.887 --> 00:52:57.959
They'd go to a place
where they could ride them.

822
00:52:58.087 --> 00:53:00.442
and Michael used to tear that thing up.

823
00:53:00.527 --> 00:53:03.519
Man. he was flying up and down
over the hills.

824
00:53:04.287 --> 00:53:07.757
I thought it was. you know. he was like
any other little boy.

825
00:53:08.127 --> 00:53:11.085
But he was a little boy with a dirt bike.

826
00:53:11.407 --> 00:53:13.682
I mean. they had two or three of 'em.

827
00:53:13.767 --> 00:53:17.237
So. when people say
that he didn't have a childhood.

828
00:53:17.687 --> 00:53:20.360
far as I'd seen he had a childhood.

829
00:53:20.447 --> 00:53:23.917
When he was a kid. things were a lot simpler.

830
00:53:24.127 --> 00:53:29.155
And I think that. as they got older.
the family became more divided

831
00:53:29.527 --> 00:53:31.483
and other stuff happened
in Michael Jackson's life

832
00:53:31.567 --> 00:53:34.127
to make him wish
that he was 12 years old again.

833
00:53:34.207 --> 00:53:37.961
So. when he says
he missed out on his childhood.

834
00:53:38.047 --> 00:53:41.562
I've always felt that what he really meant was
that he just missed it very much.

835
00:53:48.487 --> 00:53:50.364
The first time I met him was when he was 14.

836
00:53:51.527 --> 00:53:53.836
full of life. full of ambition.

837
00:53:54.967 --> 00:53:58.437
It was at the peak of his powers.

838
00:54:00.567 --> 00:54:04.446
Fire in his belly and just everything
about him was fabulous.

839
00:54:11.927 --> 00:54:14.157
I wrote it about friendship.

840
00:54:14.247 --> 00:54:17.319
The story is about this boy
who's very seriously ill

841
00:54:17.407 --> 00:54:19.637
and nothing's going right for him.

842
00:54:19.727 --> 00:54:23.515
But a little rat comes along one day.
he sees it in his bedroom.

843
00:54:24.567 --> 00:54:29.004
But it was a lovely little mousey kind of rat.

844
00:54:29.647 --> 00:54:30.966
And he befriends him.

845
00:54:31.807 --> 00:54:35.800
And it makes the boy so much better.
it lifts his spirits up.

846
00:54:35.887 --> 00:54:38.959
And that's how I wrote the song.
about friendship.

847
00:54:39.047 --> 00:54:40.275
It can be about a rat.

848
00:54:40.367 --> 00:54:43.757
"The two of us need look no more.
You're always running here and there."

849
00:54:43.847 --> 00:54:45.758
But it could be about a best friend.

850
00:54:50.967 --> 00:54:55.518
When Michael recorded Ben.
I remember going to the studio

851
00:54:55.607 --> 00:54:58.041
and it was just magical. I just loved it.

852
00:54:58.127 --> 00:55:02.245
I always remember Michael
getting very emotional about that song.

853
00:55:02.807 --> 00:55:05.640
His eyes welled up a bit.

854
00:55:05.727 --> 00:55:07.001
particularly at the middle bit.

855
00:55:07.087 --> 00:55:09.317
I'll never forget that image.

856
00:55:09.407 --> 00:55:12.717
The middle bit was.
"I used to say 'I' and 'me.'

857
00:55:12.847 --> 00:55:15.315
"now it's 'us.' now it's 'we."'

858
00:55:21.287 --> 00:55:23.596
Michael just loved those lines.

859
00:55:23.687 --> 00:55:26.838
In fact. that's why. I think.
we repeat them in the song.

860
00:55:26.967 --> 00:55:28.366
We do it again.

861
00:55:33.487 --> 00:55:36.160
There was a longing. I think.
for love and acceptance.

862
00:55:36.247 --> 00:55:38.477
going all the way back
to when he was a little kid.

863
00:55:38.567 --> 00:55:43.277
And you were able to hear that longing
in his voice.

864
00:55:43.367 --> 00:55:44.436
Singing is passion.

865
00:55:44.527 --> 00:55:45.516
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY I MOTOWN RECORDS

866
00:55:45.607 --> 00:55:46.756
You have to do it from inside of you.

867
00:55:47.527 --> 00:55:50.997
It has to come from your soul. your heart.

868
00:55:53.887 --> 00:55:55.286
And Michael Jackson had that.

869
00:55:55.367 --> 00:55:57.927
It wasn't done for the posture of "I did this."

870
00:55:58.007 --> 00:55:59.520
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

871
00:55:59.607 --> 00:56:03.077
It was done because his heart said.
"This is what I need to do." and he did it.

872
00:56:03.447 --> 00:56:04.641
Michael sings like an angel.

873
00:56:04.727 --> 00:56:06.285
He has the voice of an angel and he does...

874
00:56:06.367 --> 00:56:07.356
Kenny Gamble & Leon Huff

875
00:56:07.447 --> 00:56:08.675
PRODUCERS I SONGWRITERS.
PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

876
00:56:08.767 --> 00:56:11.281
Every note is right on it and he was doing
that at nine years old.

877
00:56:11.367 --> 00:56:13.801
I recorded Ben
I don't know how long ago.

878
00:56:13.887 --> 00:56:16.117
I mean. I hear it all the time still.
you know. go on and on and on.

879
00:56:16.207 --> 00:56:18.402
Voice of Michael Jackson
Interview courtesy of J. Randy Taraborrelli

880
00:56:18.487 --> 00:56:19.840
Yeah. it's selling more now.

881
00:56:19.927 --> 00:56:21.724
So. it's what you leave behind. I think.

882
00:56:28.327 --> 00:56:32.286
There are people who come along
once in a lifetime.

883
00:56:32.847 --> 00:56:34.997
Michael Jackson. he only happens once.

884
00:56:53.847 --> 00:56:57.078
When you think about Michael Jackson.
you think about him as a kid.

885
00:56:57.167 --> 00:56:58.156
Freda Payne
SINGER

886
00:56:58.247 --> 00:57:02.001
Like when he did some
of those earlier songs. like Ben.

887
00:57:08.647 --> 00:57:12.003
And then as he grew and evolved
and became a young man.

888
00:57:13.567 --> 00:57:16.877
I saw the metamorphosis
of a beautiful. beautiful flower.

889
00:57:16.967 --> 00:57:19.162
just blooming and unfolding.

890
00:57:24.407 --> 00:57:26.318
Michael enjoyed what he was doing.

891
00:57:26.407 --> 00:57:27.476
Mickey & Jan Rooney
JACKSON'S FRIENDS

892
00:57:27.567 --> 00:57:32.322
That's why. transition from very young
to getting older.

893
00:57:32.647 --> 00:57:38.882
it's just one year after another.
but doing what the good Lord let us do.

894
00:57:39.327 --> 00:57:42.080
When Michael became a teenager.
his voice changed.

895
00:57:42.167 --> 00:57:44.806
He realised that he would be singing
different types of music.

896
00:57:44.887 --> 00:57:45.876
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

897
00:57:45.967 --> 00:57:49.437
not kiddie pop songs
like he had been most of his career.

898
00:57:50.807 --> 00:57:54.277
The first time we worked
with the Jackson 5 was very exciting.

899
00:57:54.367 --> 00:57:56.483
Because the one thing I noticed
about the group.

900
00:57:56.567 --> 00:57:57.556
Brian & Eddie Holland

901
00:57:57.647 --> 00:57:58.636
SONGWRITERS.
HOLLAND-DOZIER-HOLLAND

902
00:57:58.727 --> 00:58:01.844
that they were extremely down to earth.
very mannerable.

903
00:58:01.927 --> 00:58:03.565
very. very polite.

904
00:58:03.647 --> 00:58:07.117
Michael recorded several songs
of mine and the Hollands'

905
00:58:07.207 --> 00:58:08.356
Lamont Dozier
SONGWRITER. HOLLAND-DOZIER-HOLLAND

906
00:58:08.447 --> 00:58:10.677
and Forever Came Today
was one of my favourites.

907
00:58:15.207 --> 00:58:18.517
He had such pipes and drama in his voice

908
00:58:18.647 --> 00:58:20.285
to be so young.

909
00:58:24.607 --> 00:58:26.837
He was just one of a kind in that respect.

910
00:58:26.927 --> 00:58:28.918
He really did the songs justice.

911
00:58:30.647 --> 00:58:34.401
I think Michael knew how important lyric
was to the song.

912
00:58:34.487 --> 00:58:35.522
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford

913
00:58:35.607 --> 00:58:37.006
SINGERS I SONGWRITERS.
'ASHFORD & SIMPSON'

914
00:58:37.087 --> 00:58:40.284
And it had to reach. touch something.
I think. for him to really wanna sing it.

915
00:58:40.367 --> 00:58:43.916
And. you know.
he'd dance and sing at the same time

916
00:58:44.007 --> 00:58:46.726
so it had to correspond with his body. too.

917
00:58:46.807 --> 00:58:49.958
So it all had to be one piece for him.

918
00:58:54.247 --> 00:58:57.478
He didn't want fluff.
He wanted something with legs on it.

919
00:58:57.567 --> 00:58:59.762
something that was gonna last through time

920
00:58:59.847 --> 00:59:02.156
and that's actually
what he ended up creating.

921
00:59:02.367 --> 00:59:06.280
The bigger he became as an artist.

922
00:59:07.047 --> 00:59:11.404
the more enamoured he seemed
to be over songwriters.

923
00:59:15.887 --> 00:59:20.165
A lot of people have done those songs
and couldn't get a handle on 'em

924
00:59:20.287 --> 00:59:22.801
like the Levi Stubbs or Diana Ross.

925
00:59:22.887 --> 00:59:26.516
but he just had a knack. a gift.

926
00:59:26.887 --> 00:59:30.084
He already had a cake
but then he put icing all on top of it.

927
00:59:34.207 --> 00:59:35.720
Around 1974.

928
00:59:36.127 --> 00:59:38.561
they started doing product at Motown
that perhaps wasn't the best.

929
00:59:38.647 --> 00:59:39.966
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

930
00:59:40.047 --> 00:59:43.483
As a fan. I loved songs
like The Boogie Man is gonna get you.

931
00:59:43.567 --> 00:59:47.196
and Lookin' through the Windows.
and Skywriter.

932
00:59:47.407 --> 00:59:49.318
but these songs weren't hits.

933
00:59:51.047 --> 00:59:52.480
Joe mentioned to me

934
00:59:52.567 --> 00:59:58.278
several times that he felt like
Motown was taking the group over.

935
00:59:58.367 --> 01:00:01.165
taking them away from his direction.

936
01:00:02.607 --> 01:00:04.279
What happened was that

937
01:00:04.367 --> 01:00:06.676
Marvin Gaye and Stevie Wonder
and Smokey Robinson

938
01:00:06.807 --> 01:00:09.367
were writing and producing
and doing a lot of things at Motown

939
01:00:09.607 --> 01:00:11.882
that the Jacksons had begun
to want to do for themselves.

940
01:00:12.247 --> 01:00:15.000
And to see how Motown treated other artists

941
01:00:15.087 --> 01:00:17.282
and how the other artists was making it.

942
01:00:17.607 --> 01:00:19.120
it was kind of disillusion.

943
01:00:21.007 --> 01:00:24.636
The company was being
run at that time by Ewart Abner.

944
01:00:24.727 --> 01:00:27.480
Berry Gordy was making movies
with Diana Ross.

945
01:00:27.887 --> 01:00:29.684
And Abner felt pretty strongly

946
01:00:29.767 --> 01:00:32.804
that they should not be writing
and producing their own music.

947
01:00:33.007 --> 01:00:35.396
that they should just
accept the material that came their way

948
01:00:35.487 --> 01:00:37.364
and just do a good job with it in the studio.

949
01:00:38.967 --> 01:00:40.639
Michael was very disillusioned.

950
01:00:41.247 --> 01:00:43.636
He wanted to not only write his own material

951
01:00:43.807 --> 01:00:45.559
but produce it as well.

952
01:00:45.647 --> 01:00:46.636
He realised

953
01:00:46.727 --> 01:00:50.276
if he was to reach these goals.
he would have to go somewhere else.

954
01:00:51.927 --> 01:00:54.521
KENNY GAMBLE:
Joe Jackson called me and told me

955
01:00:54.647 --> 01:00:56.205
that they were looking for a place to go.

956
01:00:56.287 --> 01:00:57.276
Kenny Gamble & Leon Huff

957
01:00:57.367 --> 01:00:58.595
PRODUCERS I SONGWRITERS.
PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

958
01:00:58.687 --> 01:00:59.836
And of course. Huff and myself.

959
01:00:59.927 --> 01:01:02.680
we tried to get them
for Philly International Records.

960
01:01:02.927 --> 01:01:04.838
But at the same time. CBS

961
01:01:05.087 --> 01:01:07.647
was negotiating with them also.

962
01:01:07.847 --> 01:01:09.883
I wanted to know
if there was a shot. a chance.

963
01:01:09.967 --> 01:01:11.366
Ron Alexenburg
SNR. VICE PRESIDENT CBS I EPIC RECORDS

964
01:01:11.447 --> 01:01:14.723
of being able to get involved.
And I was told there was.

965
01:01:15.927 --> 01:01:19.078
The next is. we sat down
and we started to negotiate.

966
01:01:19.767 --> 01:01:21.758
They wanted a million dollars.

967
01:01:21.847 --> 01:01:24.281
And I figured.
"Okay. that's all I could approve up to."

968
01:01:24.367 --> 01:01:25.686
That was my approval level.

969
01:01:26.247 --> 01:01:27.726
I had to go through the ranks

970
01:01:27.807 --> 01:01:31.277
and I said.
"We have a chance of signing the Jackson 5"

971
01:01:31.367 --> 01:01:33.323
and they said. "They're done."

972
01:01:33.407 --> 01:01:34.635
I said. "No. I'm sorry.

973
01:01:34.847 --> 01:01:37.407
"I believe in them.
I believe that there's a big future.

974
01:01:37.487 --> 01:01:38.920
"I believe that Michael Jackson

975
01:01:39.567 --> 01:01:42.320
"could be one of the biggest stars ever."

976
01:01:44.047 --> 01:01:45.082
That took care of that.

977
01:01:45.247 --> 01:01:48.796
I was handed the letter and they said.
"There's your deal memo. go sign 'em."

978
01:01:49.207 --> 01:01:50.526
In order to move on and progress.

979
01:01:50.607 --> 01:01:51.642
Katherine Jackson
MICHAEL'S MOTHER

980
01:01:51.727 --> 01:01:53.206
Joseph said he had to do it

981
01:01:53.287 --> 01:01:57.121
because he wanted the children
to get credit for their writings and all of that.

982
01:01:57.207 --> 01:01:58.959
and they couldn't do that at Motown.

983
01:01:59.087 --> 01:02:02.443
CBS offered them movies.
they offered 'em a TV show.

984
01:02:02.527 --> 01:02:03.960
cartoons and everything.

985
01:02:04.407 --> 01:02:07.956
And of course Gamble and Huff. you know.
we couldn't offer them all those things.

986
01:02:08.727 --> 01:02:11.605
So they decided to go with CBS.

987
01:02:11.847 --> 01:02:14.156
Probably the most important signing
of my career.

988
01:02:16.087 --> 01:02:19.636
The Jackson 5
left Motown Records and went to CBS.

989
01:02:19.807 --> 01:02:22.765
Jermaine stayed behind
because he was married to Hazel

990
01:02:23.087 --> 01:02:25.237
and Hazel was Berry Gordy's daughter.

991
01:02:26.727 --> 01:02:29.605
When my boys left Jermaine
back at Motown.

992
01:02:30.607 --> 01:02:33.121
it hurt. because Jermaine wouldn't come.

993
01:02:33.207 --> 01:02:35.960
I don't know if it was upset or angry or
whatever or disappointment or whatever.

994
01:02:36.047 --> 01:02:37.036
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

995
01:02:37.127 --> 01:02:40.437
it just was a sad time. that's all.
That's the word. It was sad.

996
01:02:41.127 --> 01:02:45.006
Jermaine felt
that he owed his allegiance to Berry

997
01:02:45.167 --> 01:02:47.840
'cause Berry was the one
that gave us our start.

998
01:02:48.567 --> 01:02:50.239
And I felt the same way.

999
01:02:50.927 --> 01:02:54.397
Berry Gordy
maintained the name "Jackson 5"

1000
01:02:54.487 --> 01:02:55.886
and they really thought that maybe

1001
01:02:56.047 --> 01:02:59.596
it wasn't fair that Berry got to keep
the name "Jackson 5."

1002
01:02:59.687 --> 01:03:02.076
so they went to CBS as the Jacksons.

1003
01:03:03.847 --> 01:03:09.638
I was not prepared
for the rubbish that would come my way.

1004
01:03:09.727 --> 01:03:12.400
It was this fear. I guess.

1005
01:03:12.487 --> 01:03:16.719
that what the supposed "lily white" company

1006
01:03:16.847 --> 01:03:19.645
was gonna do to this black family.

1007
01:03:21.047 --> 01:03:23.845
I received phone calls. I received threats.

1008
01:03:24.527 --> 01:03:27.883
There was a lot of prejudice in the business.

1009
01:03:27.967 --> 01:03:34.759
Black records usually had to cross over
from being R&B to pop stations.

1010
01:03:34.847 --> 01:03:38.157
Very rarely did a pop station
just go on a black record.

1011
01:03:38.247 --> 01:03:42.081
It's the most ridiculous thing in the world
when you think of it now

1012
01:03:42.167 --> 01:03:44.317
because it's not like that any more.

1013
01:03:44.407 --> 01:03:46.967
But it sure was in the '60s and '70s.

1014
01:03:47.287 --> 01:03:48.800
Music business was segregated

1015
01:03:48.887 --> 01:03:51.799
and even though
the Jackson 5 had crossed over.

1016
01:03:52.487 --> 01:03:55.047
there was just always
this thing that was going on

1017
01:03:55.127 --> 01:03:56.401
that there was a difference

1018
01:03:56.487 --> 01:03:59.081
between R&B and pop.

1019
01:03:59.527 --> 01:04:02.519
Forget the colour. listen to the music.

1020
01:04:02.607 --> 01:04:05.565
Does the music excite your audience?
Yes. Play it.

1021
01:04:14.167 --> 01:04:17.204
Ron Alexenburg called us and asked us

1022
01:04:17.807 --> 01:04:19.445
if we would produce them.

1023
01:04:19.607 --> 01:04:21.677
I wanted to go
to proven winners

1024
01:04:21.767 --> 01:04:24.964
and that's why I picked up the phone
and called Kenny Gamble and Leon Huff

1025
01:04:25.287 --> 01:04:28.165
and it was only at that time that I found out
that they were also

1026
01:04:28.607 --> 01:04:30.518
trying to sign the Jacksons and I said.

1027
01:04:30.607 --> 01:04:33.485
"Well. pretend that you signed them
but they're gonna be on Epic Records

1028
01:04:33.567 --> 01:04:35.285
"and please produce them for me."

1029
01:04:38.367 --> 01:04:39.356
That transition

1030
01:04:39.527 --> 01:04:41.961
was a trying time. because

1031
01:04:42.047 --> 01:04:44.607
they had a lot of emotional things
going on with them

1032
01:04:44.687 --> 01:04:49.442
because this was the first time
that Jermaine was not recording with them.

1033
01:04:49.687 --> 01:04:50.676
When Jermaine left.

1034
01:04:50.847 --> 01:04:53.486
Randy came into the group

1035
01:04:53.567 --> 01:04:59.517
and Joe had been preparing Randy.
for a long time. to become a member.

1036
01:05:00.047 --> 01:05:02.686
And he fit in like a glove.

1037
01:05:03.167 --> 01:05:05.203
This here gentleman is Randy Jackson.

1038
01:05:05.287 --> 01:05:06.276
The Jacksons
PHILADELPHIA INT. STUDIO 1977

1039
01:05:06.367 --> 01:05:09.803
and he happens to be the youngest
and the ugliest member of the Jackson 5.

1040
01:05:09.887 --> 01:05:12.481
Now what's the excuse for you. so ugly?

1041
01:05:13.687 --> 01:05:16.281
'Cause I take after my big brother. Tito.

1042
01:05:16.447 --> 01:05:20.326
As soon as we found a recording date
for an artist.

1043
01:05:20.407 --> 01:05:22.477
we would start writing for them

1044
01:05:22.567 --> 01:05:25.240
and not only would Gamble and Huff
write for them.

1045
01:05:25.327 --> 01:05:27.477
but we had McFadden and Whitehead
who wrote for them.

1046
01:05:27.767 --> 01:05:31.362
- All of our writers. all of our staff...
- Dexter. Cynthia Biggs...

1047
01:05:31.447 --> 01:05:33.517
They would know
that the Jacksons were coming in.

1048
01:05:35.447 --> 01:05:38.359
Kenny Gamble
and Leon Huff instructed me

1049
01:05:38.567 --> 01:05:40.125
to write a number one for them

1050
01:05:40.207 --> 01:05:43.597
to see if I could come up with any material
that they liked.

1051
01:05:43.687 --> 01:05:44.722
Dexter Wansel
PRODUCER I SONGWRITER

1052
01:05:44.807 --> 01:05:48.595
meaning the Jacksons.
and that Gamble and Huff could approve.

1053
01:05:48.967 --> 01:05:51.083
And so. we would have prepared for them

1054
01:05:51.967 --> 01:05:54.242
maybe 20 songs
when they walked in the door.

1055
01:05:54.327 --> 01:05:58.605
And then we'd take those 20 songs
and we'd cut 'em down to maybe. like. 12.

1056
01:05:59.047 --> 01:06:01.436
The Jacksons themselves were

1057
01:06:01.527 --> 01:06:04.564
interested in moving on with their career.

1058
01:06:04.687 --> 01:06:06.917
They wanted to write.
they wanted to produce.

1059
01:06:07.247 --> 01:06:09.761
So Huff and I. we helped them produce.

1060
01:06:09.847 --> 01:06:12.486
Tito was excellent.
'cause he's a great guitar player.

1061
01:06:12.567 --> 01:06:17.800
Kenny Gamble and Leon Huff
was very warm. nice people.

1062
01:06:17.887 --> 01:06:19.115
They had a lot of soul.

1063
01:06:19.647 --> 01:06:21.285
we had a lot in common with the music.

1064
01:06:21.367 --> 01:06:22.686
When I cut their tracks.

1065
01:06:22.807 --> 01:06:25.401
I always included Tito

1066
01:06:25.607 --> 01:06:26.960
in the rhythm section.

1067
01:06:27.047 --> 01:06:31.404
And he told me Motown would not
let him play on their tracks.

1068
01:06:31.607 --> 01:06:33.279
but he played on every one of mine.

1069
01:06:34.967 --> 01:06:39.040
Our studio was running
24 hours a day. so it was like a machine.

1070
01:06:39.367 --> 01:06:40.356
Sometimes.

1071
01:06:40.487 --> 01:06:43.923
we might wanna work until the wee hours

1072
01:06:44.207 --> 01:06:45.242
of the morning.

1073
01:06:45.327 --> 01:06:49.115
Depends on how strong
your creative juices is flowing

1074
01:06:49.287 --> 01:06:50.720
at that moment.

1075
01:06:50.807 --> 01:06:53.480
And the Jacksons were used to curfews.

1076
01:06:54.327 --> 01:06:57.000
But that changed in Philly.

1077
01:06:57.087 --> 01:06:59.396
Well. they were older.
they were teenagers then.

1078
01:06:59.487 --> 01:07:02.763
But they were still trying
to induce that old system.

1079
01:07:02.847 --> 01:07:05.520
and Michael rebelled against it.

1080
01:07:06.287 --> 01:07:09.279
Because Michael wanted to hang out

1081
01:07:10.047 --> 01:07:13.357
into the wee hours of the morning. so...
And that's what he did.

1082
01:07:13.647 --> 01:07:16.525
Michael loved his time with Gamble and Huff.

1083
01:07:16.607 --> 01:07:19.280
He really appreciated working
with two geniuses

1084
01:07:19.367 --> 01:07:21.483
who wrote so many classic songs.

1085
01:07:21.567 --> 01:07:26.163
Can you tell us. what made you want
to sing in the first place?

1086
01:07:26.247 --> 01:07:27.475
- I don't know.
- You don't know?

1087
01:07:27.567 --> 01:07:30.559
Well. you know how that goes with children.
They just don't know. do they?

1088
01:07:30.767 --> 01:07:33.520
Michael. at that time. was always shy

1089
01:07:33.647 --> 01:07:35.285
and really reserved.

1090
01:07:35.367 --> 01:07:37.961
We would say. "I wanna go get something
to eat. " or "Let's do this. "

1091
01:07:38.367 --> 01:07:40.676
And he would go. "Okay."

1092
01:07:40.927 --> 01:07:42.155
And he was very humble.

1093
01:07:42.247 --> 01:07:44.681
And I think he was pretty humble
through his life.

1094
01:07:44.767 --> 01:07:47.998
- What's your name?
- Christopher Wansel.

1095
01:07:49.367 --> 01:07:51.801
I was young when that video was made.
I was. like. one or two years old.

1096
01:07:51.887 --> 01:07:52.876
Christopher Wansel
JACKSON FRIEND

1097
01:07:52.967 --> 01:07:54.844
The relationship with the Jacksons
started there

1098
01:07:54.927 --> 01:07:56.121
and it continued throughout life.

1099
01:07:56.407 --> 01:07:57.396
Can you sing?

1100
01:07:59.367 --> 01:08:03.406
He can't dance? I wanna see his dance.

1101
01:08:03.487 --> 01:08:06.285
- Come on. man!
- You don't have to.

1102
01:08:07.327 --> 01:08:09.887
I remember a lot of just.

1103
01:08:10.247 --> 01:08:12.841
I guess. excitement and just joy
with those guys at that point. you know.

1104
01:08:12.927 --> 01:08:16.124
'cause a lot of people that would record
would be serious.

1105
01:08:16.207 --> 01:08:17.845
you wouldn't get a smile or anything.

1106
01:08:17.927 --> 01:08:19.758
but these guys were constantly joking
left and right.

1107
01:08:20.047 --> 01:08:21.526
What do you do. booger?

1108
01:08:23.287 --> 01:08:25.118
Well. other than being "the Bishop of Soul"

1109
01:08:25.207 --> 01:08:27.402
I'm also "the Monk of Funk"
and "the High Priest of Rock"

1110
01:08:27.487 --> 01:08:29.364
and "the Bishop of Soul."

1111
01:08:29.567 --> 01:08:31.159
- All right!
- Who said that?

1112
01:08:31.967 --> 01:08:34.401
I met Michael Jackson
when he first came to Philly

1113
01:08:34.487 --> 01:08:35.476
Billy Paul
ARTIST. PHILADELPHIA INT. RECORDS

1114
01:08:35.687 --> 01:08:37.484
back in. I think. it was 1974.

1115
01:08:37.807 --> 01:08:41.482
He was a very shy. young kid. you know.

1116
01:08:41.567 --> 01:08:43.842
And he was very excited to meet me.
you know.

1117
01:08:43.927 --> 01:08:47.283
'cause he... Mrs Jones...
It was at the height of Mrs Jones.

1118
01:08:47.807 --> 01:08:51.243
I welcomed him to the studio and told him
he was gonna enjoy it

1119
01:08:52.447 --> 01:08:55.245
and I'd do a good job. you know.
and he just laughed.

1120
01:08:56.367 --> 01:08:58.483
Michael's voice had changed.
obviously.

1121
01:08:58.567 --> 01:08:59.556
from the little boy

1122
01:08:59.647 --> 01:09:02.844
that could hit all those high. piercing.
I'll Be There notes

1123
01:09:03.087 --> 01:09:05.157
to a rawer sound.

1124
01:09:05.247 --> 01:09:06.839
But he was a great singer because

1125
01:09:06.967 --> 01:09:09.879
he studied the great singers.
he wanted to sing like them.

1126
01:09:10.207 --> 01:09:13.119
He knew what he wanted to do
with his voice.

1127
01:09:13.207 --> 01:09:16.836
like over-dubbing his voice
and doubling his voice

1128
01:09:16.927 --> 01:09:19.487
and speeding up one voice and this one...

1129
01:09:19.567 --> 01:09:23.560
These are things that he was telling me.
you know. We're the producers.

1130
01:09:23.647 --> 01:09:26.639
He would say.
"Gamble. can I try this? Can I try that?"

1131
01:09:26.727 --> 01:09:28.638
I said. "Yeah. try anything you want."

1132
01:09:29.847 --> 01:09:31.803
- We let him express himself.
- Yeah.

1133
01:09:31.927 --> 01:09:32.916
You know. he was in there

1134
01:09:33.327 --> 01:09:36.399
through the mixes.
he was around me and Huff all the time.

1135
01:09:36.727 --> 01:09:40.686
I remember when they were working
with Gamble and Huff in Philadelphia.

1136
01:09:40.767 --> 01:09:44.316
and I liked their sound and I liked what they
did and they helped them out a lot.

1137
01:09:44.407 --> 01:09:47.843
And that's when
the boys first start writing. too.

1138
01:09:50.127 --> 01:09:53.244
Their first record
produced by Gamble and Huff.

1139
01:09:53.327 --> 01:09:54.396
even though it went gold.

1140
01:09:54.767 --> 01:09:57.759
wasn't a really huge album for them.

1141
01:09:57.847 --> 01:10:01.123
It mid-charted in around the 50s

1142
01:10:01.367 --> 01:10:03.642
and he wanted something
that was number one.

1143
01:10:05.687 --> 01:10:08.838
When they did their second album.
Goin' Places.

1144
01:10:09.647 --> 01:10:11.638
the album was really a flop.

1145
01:10:11.727 --> 01:10:12.876
He was used to selling

1146
01:10:13.007 --> 01:10:16.079
a million or so albums on Motown.

1147
01:10:16.327 --> 01:10:18.636
And he really. in no disrespect to them.

1148
01:10:18.967 --> 01:10:24.246
wanted to produce and write
all his own material.

1149
01:10:24.327 --> 01:10:25.965
He wanted to be in charge.

1150
01:10:27.207 --> 01:10:31.405
Released in 1978 'Destiny' was the
first album produced by the Jacksons.

1151
01:10:31.487 --> 01:10:34.206
When I first heard Destiny.

1152
01:10:34.287 --> 01:10:36.676
I liked it very much.
I was very proud of them.

1153
01:10:36.807 --> 01:10:38.320
I thought they did a real good job.

1154
01:10:40.727 --> 01:10:45.198
The album re-established
The Jacksons as a top selling group.

1155
01:10:50.207 --> 01:10:53.040
He kept reaching
for higher plateaus

1156
01:10:53.327 --> 01:10:55.283
and he felt. maybe. that if the group...

1157
01:10:55.407 --> 01:10:56.442
Dennis Edwards
LEAD SINGER. 'THE TEMPTATIONS'

1158
01:10:56.527 --> 01:10:59.360
Where he wanted to go.
they probably couldn't go with him.

1159
01:10:59.607 --> 01:11:04.362
Michael was beginning
to think of himself as a solo artist

1160
01:11:04.447 --> 01:11:07.962
and I always wondered
what would happen to the brothers

1161
01:11:08.047 --> 01:11:09.400
if Michael left the group.

1162
01:11:09.487 --> 01:11:13.241
Without Michael Jackson. that was gonna be
a tough road for the Jacksons.

1163
01:11:13.327 --> 01:11:14.316
And I also believed

1164
01:11:14.407 --> 01:11:17.240
that that's one of the reasons why
Michael put it off for as long as he could.

1165
01:11:17.567 --> 01:11:18.602
Yeah. I figured he'd go solo.

1166
01:11:18.687 --> 01:11:19.836
Jimmy Ruffin
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

1167
01:11:19.927 --> 01:11:23.283
He was too good.
He couldn't carry his brothers forever.

1168
01:11:25.687 --> 01:11:27.166
One of the lawyers called me in

1169
01:11:27.487 --> 01:11:29.523
and he told me to tell the boys
to save their money

1170
01:11:29.607 --> 01:11:31.723
because Michael is gonna go solo.

1171
01:11:31.807 --> 01:11:33.525
I said. "He can't do that."

1172
01:11:33.607 --> 01:11:35.598
And he said.
"Well. he don't need his brothers."

1173
01:11:36.527 --> 01:11:38.245
I said. "They need one another."

1174
01:11:38.847 --> 01:11:42.044
Joseph just felt
that what was really important

1175
01:11:42.127 --> 01:11:44.800
wasn't the individual success of the group

1176
01:11:45.127 --> 01:11:49.837
but it was the group itself
and it was the family itself.

1177
01:11:49.927 --> 01:11:55.047
And that's easy to say
when you're not the lead singer of the group.

1178
01:11:55.647 --> 01:11:59.640
I saw Michael leaving
his father as a positive.

1179
01:11:59.727 --> 01:12:02.719
no longer persecuting him. abusing him

1180
01:12:03.007 --> 01:12:07.125
or saying things to him that were ugly.

1181
01:12:07.207 --> 01:12:10.643
He seemed to only be
getting it from one source. his father.

1182
01:12:10.847 --> 01:12:13.566
Michael never felt comfortable
with Joe as his manager.

1183
01:12:13.647 --> 01:12:14.966
'cause he was afraid of him.

1184
01:12:15.047 --> 01:12:18.039
And when you're afraid of somebody.
you don't wanna be around them.

1185
01:12:18.287 --> 01:12:20.926
That was his destiny. to be by himself.

1186
01:12:21.007 --> 01:12:23.202
His confidence level was really high

1187
01:12:23.287 --> 01:12:26.279
and when he made the transition
from us to Quincy.

1188
01:12:26.367 --> 01:12:27.402
he was ready.

1189
01:12:31.887 --> 01:12:34.481
Michael really admired Quincy Jones.

1190
01:12:35.327 --> 01:12:36.442
Because

1191
01:12:36.727 --> 01:12:38.604
Quincy had produced Frank Sinatra.

1192
01:12:39.167 --> 01:12:40.156
icon.

1193
01:12:40.807 --> 01:12:41.796
Ella Fitzgerald.

1194
01:12:42.287 --> 01:12:43.356
icon.

1195
01:12:43.607 --> 01:12:44.642
Dinah Washington.

1196
01:12:44.767 --> 01:12:45.836
icon.

1197
01:12:45.927 --> 01:12:51.320
And so many other acts
during his very illustrious career.

1198
01:12:53.207 --> 01:12:56.279
When he was about to do Off The Wall.
he went to him.

1199
01:12:57.007 --> 01:12:58.838
asking for suggestions

1200
01:12:59.327 --> 01:13:03.240
of people that might be interested
in working with him.

1201
01:13:03.327 --> 01:13:08.355
And the story goes that Quincy Jones said.
"I'm available." and he said.

1202
01:13:08.967 --> 01:13:10.798
"I would love to work with you."

1203
01:13:11.967 --> 01:13:15.482
I was in the studio
for the Off The Wall sessions.

1204
01:13:15.687 --> 01:13:19.965
and so. I was able to actually watch
Michael and Quincy work together.

1205
01:13:20.047 --> 01:13:25.405
And Michael really thought of Quincy
as sort of the father that he hoped

1206
01:13:25.687 --> 01:13:27.678
Joseph could have been for him.

1207
01:13:27.767 --> 01:13:30.440
One of the things that Michael told me
he loved about working with Quincy

1208
01:13:30.527 --> 01:13:34.236
was that Quincy thought
Michael's ideas were good ideas.

1209
01:13:35.047 --> 01:13:37.402
And if you listen to some of the demos.

1210
01:13:37.527 --> 01:13:41.076
those songs were complete
when Michael brought them to Quincy.

1211
01:13:41.167 --> 01:13:42.759
I mean. you could have just put them out.

1212
01:13:43.167 --> 01:13:46.364
And Quincy appreciated the fact
that Michael had this amazing ability.

1213
01:13:46.607 --> 01:13:48.006
There was a lot of respect there.

1214
01:13:48.847 --> 01:13:52.044
Quincy Jones has always been
smart about merging what he has to offer

1215
01:13:52.287 --> 01:13:53.436
with what the artist has to offer

1216
01:13:53.527 --> 01:13:55.245
and I think that's probably
one of Quincy's greatest gifts.

1217
01:13:55.327 --> 01:13:56.316
Peabo Bryson
SINGER

1218
01:13:56.407 --> 01:13:58.602
And he certainly did that with Michael
in abundance.

1219
01:14:00.007 --> 01:14:02.885
I will never forget when
he brought Off The Wall over to my house

1220
01:14:03.087 --> 01:14:06.045
to play it for me.

1221
01:14:06.127 --> 01:14:12.202
It just jumped right out of the record player.

1222
01:14:12.287 --> 01:14:17.964
It was the most unbelievable album

1223
01:14:18.047 --> 01:14:19.480
I'd ever heard to that date.

1224
01:14:19.567 --> 01:14:21.762
To me. that's one of the greatest albums
I've ever heard in my life.

1225
01:14:21.847 --> 01:14:23.200
Russell Thompkins. Jr.
LEAD SINGER. 'THE STYLISTICS'

1226
01:14:23.287 --> 01:14:24.276
When the musicians that I know.

1227
01:14:24.367 --> 01:14:28.724
and we all sit around
and we listen to the arrangements.

1228
01:14:29.167 --> 01:14:32.603
and the production that was done on that
album. the things that Quincy Jones did.

1229
01:14:32.807 --> 01:14:33.876
was fantastic.

1230
01:14:34.007 --> 01:14:36.441
Quincy Jones had horn players
playing such fantastic licks

1231
01:14:36.527 --> 01:14:37.562
Martha Reeves
ARTIST. MOTOWN RECORDS

1232
01:14:37.647 --> 01:14:41.356
and had drummers and percussions
that Michael had to dance to.

1233
01:14:41.447 --> 01:14:44.200
and that only made him
even the more exciting.

1234
01:14:44.607 --> 01:14:47.679
Quincy was a great arranger.

1235
01:14:47.767 --> 01:14:52.283
Michael was a great singer.
and also had a great foresight

1236
01:14:52.367 --> 01:14:54.562
and it just was a marriage made in heaven.

1237
01:14:55.967 --> 01:14:57.116
I had the pleasure

1238
01:14:57.207 --> 01:14:58.925
of coming up in the same era
and watching him

1239
01:14:59.007 --> 01:14:59.996
Eddie Floyd
SINGER I SONGWRITER. STAX RECORDS

1240
01:15:00.087 --> 01:15:02.726
and once he got with Michael... Wow...

1241
01:15:02.927 --> 01:15:04.519
History speaks for itself.

1242
01:15:05.607 --> 01:15:06.676
There was just no way

1243
01:15:07.047 --> 01:15:08.799
that these songs
weren't going to be big hits.

1244
01:15:10.967 --> 01:15:13.640
An album would have
two very good songs on it

1245
01:15:14.047 --> 01:15:17.835
that they know is gonna be hits.
and then they throw anything on an album.

1246
01:15:18.007 --> 01:15:19.281
to fill it out.

1247
01:15:19.367 --> 01:15:23.155
And he said. "Mother. I don't believe in that.
I think every song should be a hit."

1248
01:15:23.327 --> 01:15:26.319
And so. he just put good songs out there
and gave the people

1249
01:15:26.407 --> 01:15:27.806
good product.

1250
01:15:30.847 --> 01:15:33.998
Actually. it made me start dancing again

1251
01:15:34.087 --> 01:15:35.076
when I went out.

1252
01:15:35.167 --> 01:15:38.762
'cause I was one of those
"I don't wanna sweat" guys.

1253
01:15:38.847 --> 01:15:41.441
When Off The Wall was on.
you had to hit the dance floor.

1254
01:15:41.687 --> 01:15:43.086
It was just absolutely astounding

1255
01:15:43.167 --> 01:15:45.522
and then he just
kept getting better and better.

1256
01:15:45.607 --> 01:15:46.596
Abdul 'Duke' Fakir
ARTIST. 'THE FOUR TOPS'

1257
01:15:48.007 --> 01:15:51.079
Such a God-given talent. so precious.

1258
01:15:52.487 --> 01:15:55.399
When he recorded Thriller.
Michael was very excited

1259
01:15:55.527 --> 01:15:56.516
and he said that he thought

1260
01:15:56.647 --> 01:15:59.480
this was going to sell hundreds
and hundreds of millions of copies.

1261
01:15:59.927 --> 01:16:03.203
Quincy kept telling Michael.
"You know what? Maybe five million.

1262
01:16:04.327 --> 01:16:06.283
"I mean. if we do 10 million.
it's gonna be huge.

1263
01:16:06.367 --> 01:16:07.766
"but. you know. don't get your hopes up."

1264
01:16:08.127 --> 01:16:10.687
He was never pleased
with what he accomplished.

1265
01:16:10.767 --> 01:16:13.645
He always wanted
to accomplish the impossible.

1266
01:16:14.447 --> 01:16:19.077
Michael felt that Quincy
should have been on his team

1267
01:16:19.647 --> 01:16:21.205
with 100 million.

1268
01:16:21.287 --> 01:16:23.278
And he told his attorney.

1269
01:16:23.527 --> 01:16:26.439
"Thriller's not coming out.
Quincy doesn't believe in it.

1270
01:16:26.727 --> 01:16:28.763
"Cancel. The thing's not coming out." right?

1271
01:16:29.647 --> 01:16:31.956
So. Michael had a conversation
with Walter Yetnikoff.

1272
01:16:32.047 --> 01:16:34.038
who was running CBS at that time.

1273
01:16:34.127 --> 01:16:38.325
And Walter Yetnikoff told Michael.
"Look. who cares what these guys think.

1274
01:16:38.407 --> 01:16:42.116
"It's not about what their impression is
of this music.

1275
01:16:42.207 --> 01:16:44.084
"it's what you believe to be the case.

1276
01:16:44.167 --> 01:16:45.998
"And if you believe this is
going to sell 100 million copies.

1277
01:16:46.087 --> 01:16:47.076
"guess what. Michael?

1278
01:16:47.207 --> 01:16:48.356
"I'm with you.

1279
01:16:48.447 --> 01:16:52.201
"Let this thing come out.
Don't mess with this. Just let it come out."

1280
01:16:52.327 --> 01:16:53.316
And then Michael did.

1281
01:16:53.647 --> 01:16:55.046
But it could have gone either way.

1282
01:16:55.247 --> 01:17:00.844
We were averaging a million units a week.
which no other record had done.

1283
01:17:00.927 --> 01:17:01.916
Frank Dileo
JACKSON'S MANAGER 1984-89. 2009

1284
01:17:05.127 --> 01:17:10.155
Michael Jackson. that year with Thriller.
saved the record business.

1285
01:17:10.247 --> 01:17:12.283
Tower Records was going out of business.

1286
01:17:12.527 --> 01:17:18.443
CBS itself had had two black Fridays
where they laid off. like. a thousand people.

1287
01:17:18.527 --> 01:17:23.203
other companies were laying off people.
Everybody was losing their job.

1288
01:17:23.287 --> 01:17:25.164
But Thriller was so big.

1289
01:17:25.927 --> 01:17:30.557
it brought millions of people into the stores

1290
01:17:31.007 --> 01:17:34.556
and they not only bought Thriller.
they bought other product.

1291
01:17:34.767 --> 01:17:38.885
It was the music that will probably
influence contemporary artists

1292
01:17:38.967 --> 01:17:41.401
for a long. long time to come.

1293
01:17:41.487 --> 01:17:45.765
It gave us a...

1294
01:17:45.847 --> 01:17:49.237
A goal. a bull's-eye or a dream to get to.

1295
01:17:49.527 --> 01:17:50.960
something to aspire to.

1296
01:17:51.687 --> 01:17:54.804
After Michael made Off The Wall.
and then Thriller.

1297
01:17:55.287 --> 01:17:59.997
I knew then that it was like shooting a rocket
up to the moon.

1298
01:18:03.527 --> 01:18:04.846
Were you aware of the sales?

1299
01:18:05.167 --> 01:18:07.886
I pretty much did the album
and just sat back and watched.

1300
01:18:08.847 --> 01:18:10.041
He saw where he wanted to go

1301
01:18:10.127 --> 01:18:11.116
Freda Payne
SINGER

1302
01:18:11.247 --> 01:18:12.316
and he went there.

1303
01:18:12.647 --> 01:18:13.682
And nobody could stop him.

1304
01:18:17.807 --> 01:18:19.684
He went to a level

1305
01:18:19.927 --> 01:18:21.883
that only the very great have obtained.

1306
01:18:25.807 --> 01:18:27.877
He wanted to be the best
and he was the best.

1307
01:18:32.407 --> 01:18:34.921
God took that little man
and he says.

1308
01:18:35.287 --> 01:18:37.562
"Okay now. you take over the music world."

1309
01:18:37.647 --> 01:18:38.636
Bobby Taylor
ARTIST. GORDY I MOTOWN RECORDS

1310
01:18:38.807 --> 01:18:40.035
"It now belongs to you."

1311
01:18:42.607 --> 01:18:44.643
What made him so special

1312
01:18:45.047 --> 01:18:46.685
is that he was held back

1313
01:18:47.247 --> 01:18:48.475
for so long

1314
01:18:48.567 --> 01:18:51.400
that when he was finally released.
all of it came out.

1315
01:18:52.767 --> 01:18:54.758
He just lit the stage on fire.

1316
01:18:55.167 --> 01:18:58.239
He stole the show from everybody.
including the Jackson 5.

1317
01:18:58.327 --> 01:18:59.316
Tito Jackson
MICHAEL'S BROTHER

1318
01:19:00.767 --> 01:19:02.405
Michael was into his fans.

1319
01:19:03.007 --> 01:19:05.646
To make all these people that happy.
it charged him up. it really did.

1320
01:19:05.727 --> 01:19:06.876
Ronnie Rancifer
KEYBOARDIST. 'JACKSON 5' 1967-77

1321
01:19:09.327 --> 01:19:12.797
My fondest memory
is the Motown 25.

1322
01:19:12.887 --> 01:19:14.923
Yeah.
We were on that show.

1323
01:19:15.007 --> 01:19:15.996
- and he premiered the moonwalk. Wow.
- That was something.

1324
01:19:16.087 --> 01:19:17.076
Valerie Simpson & Nickolas Ashford.

1325
01:19:17.167 --> 01:19:18.156
SINGERS I SONGWRITERS.
'ASHFORD & SIMPSON'

1326
01:19:21.887 --> 01:19:22.876
Michael called me

1327
01:19:23.367 --> 01:19:26.120
when he got home from doing Motown 25.

1328
01:19:26.207 --> 01:19:27.606
and said. "I've just given
the greatest performance of my life."

1329
01:19:27.687 --> 01:19:28.676
David Gest
MICHAEL'S CLOSE FRIEND

1330
01:19:33.047 --> 01:19:35.561
How excited we all were for him.

1331
01:19:35.927 --> 01:19:38.646
it was like. "I guess I've arrived."
you know?

1332
01:19:38.727 --> 01:19:41.082
Dionne Warwick
SINGER

1333
01:19:41.207 --> 01:19:43.926
With an armful of Grammys.
It was wonderful.

1334
01:19:44.807 --> 01:19:47.799
In 1984 Michael won an unprecedented
8 Grammys for 'Thriller'.

1335
01:19:51.687 --> 01:19:54.997
'Thriller' became the best selling album
of all time with sales exceeding 110 million.

1336
01:19:56.447 --> 01:19:57.436
Michael!

1337
01:19:58.847 --> 01:20:02.044
During the eighties Michael had more
number 1 hits than any other artist.

1338
01:20:07.207 --> 01:20:08.765
Michael Jackson is

1339
01:20:08.967 --> 01:20:12.164
one of the greatest artists of all time.

1340
01:20:12.247 --> 01:20:16.604
who transcended being labelled
black. white. red. yellow.

1341
01:20:16.687 --> 01:20:20.839
it didn't matter.
he appealed to everybody. everywhere.

1342
01:20:21.207 --> 01:20:26.565
I think he came here ready
'cause he always wanted to be a superstar.

1343
01:20:26.647 --> 01:20:31.243
He was wearing little rings on his fingers
when he was a little man. you know.

1344
01:20:31.847 --> 01:20:33.565
He was very conscious

1345
01:20:33.967 --> 01:20:36.037
of the iconoclastic nature
of "Michael Jackson."

1346
01:20:36.127 --> 01:20:37.116
J. Randy Taraborrelli
JACKSON FRIEND AND BIOGRAPHER

1347
01:20:38.367 --> 01:20:40.562
and what it would mean historically.

1348
01:20:40.887 --> 01:20:42.764
Michael's image
was very important to him

1349
01:20:42.887 --> 01:20:45.162
because Fred Astaire
and the people that he studied.

1350
01:20:45.567 --> 01:20:47.683
Jackie Wilson. James Brown...

1351
01:20:47.847 --> 01:20:51.726
How are they being revered? Why are they
so terrific and what did they do?

1352
01:20:51.807 --> 01:20:52.796
And he was a great student.

1353
01:20:52.887 --> 01:20:54.286
Ron Alexenburg
SNR. VICE PRESIDENT CBS I EPIC RECORDS

1354
01:20:54.367 --> 01:20:55.641
It just didn't come upon him.

1355
01:20:55.727 --> 01:20:58.002
he studied his craft. he worked at it.

1356
01:20:58.367 --> 01:21:00.085
He was directing his career.

1357
01:21:00.567 --> 01:21:03.320
he was so street smart

1358
01:21:03.407 --> 01:21:09.357
and he knew how to make a campaign work.
and more importantly. how to make it last.

1359
01:21:09.687 --> 01:21:13.362
He believed that the biggest stars
left the biggest impression

1360
01:21:13.447 --> 01:21:16.041
and it was bigger than just their art.
you know.

1361
01:21:16.127 --> 01:21:18.595
What you thought of instantly

1362
01:21:19.127 --> 01:21:20.879
when you thought of these celebrities

1363
01:21:20.967 --> 01:21:23.606
and with Michael.
what you began to think of instantly

1364
01:21:23.687 --> 01:21:26.121
was the fedora hat. it was the one glove.

1365
01:21:26.687 --> 01:21:30.157
On the show that we did together
at Madison Square Garden.

1366
01:21:30.247 --> 01:21:32.044
he came out with a suitcase

1367
01:21:32.487 --> 01:21:36.366
and inside was the glove.
and he had the hat.

1368
01:21:37.487 --> 01:21:41.400
and he had everything he needed
to show them.

1369
01:21:41.487 --> 01:21:44.638
"Nobody does it better than I
and these are my trademarks."

1370
01:21:45.087 --> 01:21:48.557
The total package
of Michael Jackson became very important.

1371
01:21:48.647 --> 01:21:51.286
especially with the advent of video culture.

1372
01:21:51.447 --> 01:21:53.642
which happened at the exact same time

1373
01:21:53.727 --> 01:21:56.321
that Billie Jean and Beat It
were becoming hit records.

1374
01:21:57.927 --> 01:22:02.478
'Billie Jean' was the 1st video by a black
artist to receive heavy rotation on MTV.

1375
01:22:05.567 --> 01:22:09.037
Michael never officially left The Jacksons.
'Victory' (1984) was their last album together.

1376
01:22:14.367 --> 01:22:19.077
It was an immense pressure
to be in the public eye

1377
01:22:19.167 --> 01:22:22.045
and he kept wanting
to look better and better.

1378
01:22:22.447 --> 01:22:24.722
He was very. very self-conscious.

1379
01:22:24.847 --> 01:22:27.680
Michael felt under pressure

1380
01:22:27.807 --> 01:22:30.526
where his image was concerned

1381
01:22:31.007 --> 01:22:32.156
because of who he is.

1382
01:22:32.247 --> 01:22:35.876
He was a black guy. he was an inner-city guy.

1383
01:22:35.967 --> 01:22:38.401
How could he be the darling
of white society?

1384
01:22:39.087 --> 01:22:40.281
He had to change.

1385
01:22:42.047 --> 01:22:47.963
I think all that was what led
to the first plastic surgery. in 1978.

1386
01:22:48.167 --> 01:22:50.237
I went to interview Michael
at his home in Encino

1387
01:22:50.327 --> 01:22:52.841
and he showed up at the door
with bandages on his face

1388
01:22:52.927 --> 01:22:54.519
and his eyes were black and blue.

1389
01:22:54.607 --> 01:22:56.802
and I thought that he had been
in some kind of a fight.

1390
01:22:58.087 --> 01:23:01.762
He explained to me
that he had fallen on stage

1391
01:23:02.287 --> 01:23:03.800
and broke his nose.

1392
01:23:03.887 --> 01:23:06.481
This was why he had that first surgery.

1393
01:23:08.607 --> 01:23:11.485
His next major one was in 1981

1394
01:23:11.567 --> 01:23:14.286
and he stayed with me for four weeks.
I took care of him.

1395
01:23:14.807 --> 01:23:18.482
I always felt that he looked so good
after that second one.

1396
01:23:18.567 --> 01:23:19.841
he never needed to do more.

1397
01:23:20.447 --> 01:23:21.596
And then after that.

1398
01:23:21.687 --> 01:23:23.678
there were all kinds of other things
that were going on

1399
01:23:23.767 --> 01:23:26.122
that it was really hard to determine.

1400
01:23:26.767 --> 01:23:28.917
you know. what he was doing
and when he was doing it.

1401
01:23:36.607 --> 01:23:38.916
I think he should have stopped
before he did. yes.

1402
01:23:39.007 --> 01:23:42.443
Being vulnerable and listening to others.
